00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:08.040
[Guest]: So, you know, so if you know, if you look at it from what you just said, this seems

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:15.800
[Guest]: to have a structure of a Ponzi scheme and so which is where it is important to differentiate,

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:20.960
[Guest]: you know, Ponzi schemes can be fraudulent and then there can be schemes which have a

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:25.520
[Guest]: structure of a Ponzi scheme, but the idea is not to defraud anyone.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:29.620
[Guest]: So in this case, obviously, you know, the idea is not to defraud anyone.

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:35.560
[Guest]: But if you look at the overall structure of all these platform companies, they have a

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:37.280
[Guest]: very, very Ponzi structure.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:39.200
[Guest]: Now, why is that?

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:46.080
[Guest]: That is simply because, you know, what they are aiming for is a monopoly in their line

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:47.080
[Guest]: of business.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:53.120
[Guest]: Now, there's a concept called network externality, which basically means that, you know, with

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:58.840
[Guest]: every extra user on a particular network, the value of that network goes up.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:04.880
[Guest]: So to give you a, you know, a very, very simple example, Alexander Graham Bell invented the

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:05.880
[Guest]: telephone.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:11.040
[Guest]: Now, if only Mr. Graham Bell continued to have the telephone, it wouldn't have made

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:12.040
[Guest]: any sense.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:15.600
[Guest]: But let's say, you know, one more guy started having a telephone.

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:20.400
[Guest]: So then Mr. Graham Bell could talk to that guy, then another guy, you know, had a telephone

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:21.400
[Guest]: and so on.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:25.720
[Guest]: So more the number of people, you know, who had a telephone, the more the value of the

00:10:25.720 --> 00:10:32.280
[Guest]: telephone went up, or to give you a more contemporary example, all of us are, you know, there on

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:35.040
[Guest]: Facebook, because all of us are there on Facebook, right?

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:43.240
[Guest]: We're not there on any other social media network of the kind that Facebook is.

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:48.160
[Guest]: There were other networks of that kind, there was MySpace, there was Orkut, which was particularly,

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:51.440
[Guest]: you know, very, very popular in India.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:56.880
[Guest]: But once Facebook sort of became the place to be in, everyone sort of moved to Facebook.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:01.040
[Guest]: Now, what happens here is now, how does it apply in Oyo's case?

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:07.800
[Guest]: Now, Oyo is in the business of renting out hotel rooms, okay.

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:13.280
[Guest]: So obviously, it needs hotels to list on the website.

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:17.520
[Guest]: And it also needs people to come onto the website and book those rooms.

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:20.800
[Guest]: Now, so basically supply and demand.

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:22.600
[Guest]: Now, how does it create demand?

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:29.400
[Guest]: It creates demand by offering discounts, so that people come in and book rooms on Oyo.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:36.080
[Guest]: So the more people who come on to Oyo to book rooms, the more, you know, hotels should be

00:11:36.080 --> 00:11:40.760
[Guest]: interested in listing themselves on Oyo.

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:47.440
[Guest]: And now, how do you get more people to sort of come on to the network is by offering huge

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:49.320
[Guest]: discounts.

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest]: And what happens is that the discounts are so huge, and not just in case of Oyo, I mean,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.240
[Guest]: it works across any other, you know, platform company, you know, right from the way Uber

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:09.280
[Guest]: and Ola started to how Swiggy and Zomato are working right now, is, I mean, you offer large

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:16.600
[Guest]: discounts and because of that, you face what is known as high cash burn rate, okay.

00:12:16.600 --> 00:12:23.240
[Guest]: Now, this is just basically a jargon, which the platform guys use for, you know, for a

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:27.640
[Guest]: simple word of operating losses, I mean, you operate at a level where the price that you

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:30.200
[Guest]: sell your product at is not profitable.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:35.920
[Guest]: Now, in order to keep going, they need new money to keep coming in.

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:42.520
[Guest]: And as long as the new money that keeps coming in is greater than the cash burn rate, the

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:44.360
[Guest]: company keeps operating.

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:49.560
[Guest]: So which is why, you know, if you look at Oyo, given their international aspirations,

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:55.560
[Guest]: they need a lot of money because, you know, how do you get people on to Oyo if you don't

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:57.320
[Guest]: offer discounts?

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:02.320
[Guest]: So if you look at the structure, the structure is very similar to that of a Ponzi scheme

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:08.400
[Guest]: where the money being brought in by investors, as long as it is greater than the money going

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:12.480
[Guest]: out, which is basically the losses that the company is facing, the company keeps running.

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:20.000
[Guest]: Now, the aim here is to become a monopoly in that particular area and then sort of make

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.940
[Guest]: all the money that you can, I mean, monopolies can simply make money by existing.

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:26.920
[Guest]: So that is what every VC wants.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:31.160
[Guest]: That is what every leader of a platform company wants.

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:37.560
[Guest]: Now, the thing is, it doesn't, you know, it happens, but it doesn't happen with all companies

00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:38.640
[Guest]: and not all the time.

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:41.160
[Guest]: So let's take the example of the search engine business.

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:45.120
[Guest]: Now, you and I will remember that when the internet first came to India, there was nothing

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:46.120
[Guest]: like Google.

00:13:46.120 --> 00:13:50.480
[Guest]: There was, you know, there was AltaVista, there was Yahoo, there was even something

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:52.760
[Guest]: called AskJeeves.com.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:58.080
[Guest]: And then Google came along in 2000 and gradually took over the entire business.

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:04.040
[Guest]: And now the only search engine that, you know, most of the world uses is Google, unless you

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:05.040
[Guest]: are in China.

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:08.040
[Guest]: I mean, then that's a different story.

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:13.560
[Guest]: So Google makes monopoly profits, same is the case with Amazon.

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:21.480
[Guest]: So the way the entire platform business has evolved is, you know, is very, very Ponzi

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:24.240
[Guest]: in structure, because everyone wants to be a monopoly.

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:28.680
[Amit Varma]: So I think in the course of your explanation, there are basically four separate kind of

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:33.240
[Amit Varma]: points that you're making, and I'd like to sort of break them up one by one.

00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:38.680
[Amit Varma]: One is, of course, a standard Ponzi scheme, where you correctly point out that a Ponzi

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:41.480
[Amit Varma]: structure may not always be part of a fraud.

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:47.560
[Amit Varma]: In this case, the structure that Ritesh Agarwal used to buy back his shares is like a Ponzi

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:55.600
[Amit Varma]: structure in the sense that he is first, you know, using his existing stake to buy a further

00:14:55.600 --> 00:15:00.360
[Amit Varma]: stake and then using that to buy further and so on and so forth, which has a very Ponzi

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:01.360
[Amit Varma]: like feel to it.

