[Amit Varma]: The second point is about network externalities, which, you know, is something that all networks

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:11.760
[Amit Varma]: obviously.

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:17.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I mean, that's how these big sites like Amazon and eBay and what OYO is attempting

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:20.000
[Amit Varma]: to do and Somato and so on, that's kind of how they function.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And there's nothing about it, which is not legit, it's standard, it's, you know, there's

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:32.600
[Amit Varma]: nothing per se, wrong with that logic, and I don't even know why it's Ponzi-like.

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:39.600
[Amit Varma]: What you sort of refer to as Ponzi-like is, I think, and which I was going to ask you

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:45.160
[Amit Varma]: about separately anyway, is that the structure through which these guys get one round of

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:49.480
[Amit Varma]: investing and then another and then another, which is really the greater fool theory where

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:51.200
[Amit Varma]: everyone is investing.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And in some cases, you don't really care whether the business is viable at that stage or is

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:56.880
[Amit Varma]: ever going to be viable.

00:15:56.880 --> 00:16:01.480
[Amit Varma]: All you want is at a later stage of funding, you can sell your share and move on.

00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:05.920
[Guest]: So basically, all you want is that, you know, you put your money and then that money leads

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:07.640
[Guest]: to more monopoly.

00:16:07.640 --> 00:16:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And then that leads to a greater valuation and then you can eventually...

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Correct.

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:17.760
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, so a lot of the for example, Ritesh Agarwal's buyback of his shares is actually

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:20.200
[Amit Varma]: the people he's buying out are the early investors of the company.

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:25.920
[Amit Varma]: So even if OYO eventually fails, those the early investors can all say that we made a

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:29.320
[Amit Varma]: wise choice because they actually sold at a profit, they invested something, they sold

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:35.200
[Amit Varma]: at a profit, maybe they sold to, you know, SoftBank or to Ritesh Agarwal himself, it

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:36.200
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter.

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:40.360
[Amit Varma]: Ritesh Agarwal, of course, he's getting the financing for this from Nomura, which has

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:42.720
[Amit Varma]: a heavy SoftBank investment.

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:49.440
[Amit Varma]: And I find it sort of hard to comprehend how they can be a greater fool in the sense at

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:53.960
[Amit Varma]: this scale, there is no one SoftBank can sell these shares to, where is the cash out for

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:58.240
[Amit Varma]: them, unless they do an IPO at insane valuations and common investors.

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:03.440
[Guest]: Which is what happened to Uber, I mean, if you look at Uber, Uber was being financed

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:05.800
[Guest]: by all these VCs.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:06.800
[Guest]: Including SoftBank.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:07.800
[Guest]: Including SoftBank.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.000
[Guest]: And now it's being financed by the shareholders.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:15.120
[Guest]: I mean, the losses in the last quarter were $5 billion.

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

00:17:16.120 --> 00:17:17.120
[Amit Varma]: So...

00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:18.120
[Guest]: And the IPO got cancelled.

00:17:18.120 --> 00:17:19.120
[Guest]: So...

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:20.120
[Amit Varma]: The WeWork IPO went through.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:21.120
[Amit Varma]: The WeWork IPO got cancelled.

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:22.120
[Guest]: Oh, sorry, sorry.

00:17:22.120 --> 00:17:23.120
[Guest]: My bad.

00:17:23.120 --> 00:17:24.120
[Unknown]: You're confusing.

00:17:24.120 --> 00:17:28.720
[Guest]: So Uber, in fact, even had a line in their prospectus, which said that we might never

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:29.720
[Guest]: make money.

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:30.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:31.720
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:17:31.720 --> 00:17:37.720
[Amit Varma]: So, the fourth point that you raised that I kind of want to talk about is the monopolies

00:17:37.720 --> 00:17:38.720
[Amit Varma]: aspect.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:45.160
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, every business wants a monopoly, though the thing here is that a monopoly is

00:17:45.160 --> 00:17:47.880
[Amit Varma]: only problematic when consumers suffer.

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:53.000
[Amit Varma]: The argument I would make in the case of the seeming monopolies that Amazon and Google

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:00.880
[Amit Varma]: have built up is that, number one, they are monopolies only if you sort of consider what

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:02.480
[Amit Varma]: they are doing in a narrow way.

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:05.620
[Amit Varma]: For example, Facebook is a monopoly in social media, yeah.

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:09.200
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that they're not a monopoly when it comes to how do you spend your time

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:13.080
[Amit Varma]: or how you connect with others or how you communicate with others, where there is a

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:14.080
[Amit Varma]: lot of competition.

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:16.080
[Amit Varma]: So in that strict sense, they're not a monopoly.

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:18.360
[Amit Varma]: Second, there are no barriers to entry.

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:22.160
[Amit Varma]: Other people can and do enter all the time.

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:26.760
[Amit Varma]: And even a seeming monopoly at a particular point in time, like Microsoft once, may be

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:29.720
[Amit Varma]: completely irrelevant a decade later.

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:33.640
[Amit Varma]: And the third point is that as far as any of these so-called Internet monopolies are

00:18:33.640 --> 00:18:37.720
[Amit Varma]: concerned, we are still getting extremely cheap prices from Amazon.

00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:40.640
[Amit Varma]: We are still getting Google search delivered to us free.

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.760
[Amit Varma]: We are still, you know, not having to pay for Facebook.

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:49.400
[Amit Varma]: So I don't really, I mean, first of all, I would object to the definition of those companies

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:50.400
[Amit Varma]: as monopolies.

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:55.080
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, I would say that, you know, there are no barriers to entry as such.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:59.480
[Amit Varma]: And as long as consumers don't suffer for it, like I hear a lot of alarmists talk about

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:03.680
[Amit Varma]: how that they will now spend VC money, they will build up a monopoly and after they have

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:08.120
[Amit Varma]: driven everyone out of the market, they will raise prices, and consumers will suffer.

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:11.520
[Guest]: But the point is, no one actually in this, among these Internet companies actually raise

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:12.520
[Guest]: prices.

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:13.520
[Guest]: No, I don't agree on that.

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:19.440
[Guest]: If you look at what is happening with Uber and Ola, and at least in the last one year,

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:22.360
[Guest]: is that prices have gone up dramatically.

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:26.960
[Guest]: And now it's reached a stage where, because they've managed to destroy, and I'm talking

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:31.480
[Guest]: about Mumbai here, not the other cities, because they've managed to destroy a large part of

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:36.040
[Guest]: the normal Kali Pili business, there is an overall shortage of cabs.

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:41.040
[Guest]: So you get so earlier, what used to happen was the P cars used to start sometime in,

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:42.040
[Guest]: you know, in the evening.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: Now there are, you know, prices are high, almost all through the day.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:52.160
[Guest]: So there are I mean, so there are issues, it's not as straightforward as I agree with

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:53.160
[Guest]: you on Google.

00:19:53.160 --> 00:19:58.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, but my argument about Uber and Ola is that number one, they brought a necessary

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:01.280
[Amit Varma]: disruption and raise the supply and the supply is still higher.

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, when I left home today, I didn't feel like driving, I was guaranteed

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:10.680
[Amit Varma]: an Uber, maybe I paid more for it than I would have liked to because of peak surcharge, but

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:11.680
[Amit Varma]: fine.

00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And I could also have taken an auto but the point is the autos were there if I was in

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:18.000
[Amit Varma]: South Mumbai, I would also get the Kali Pili.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.800
[Amit Varma]: What has happened is that the supply has gone up the number of people who can rely on public

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:27.000
[Amit Varma]: transport has gone up massively like so many women tell me that they feel much safer because

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:31.560
[Amit Varma]: along with all the other options which still exist, they also have the relative safety

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:33.240
[Amit Varma]: of an Uber or an Ola.

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:37.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they have added to the options and I won't be convinced that they've actually

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:42.400
[Amit Varma]: made the public transportation market worse till I actually see data on it.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:48.680
[Amit Varma]: Because my anecdotal experience sort of indicates that, you know, but anyway, I mean, that's

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:52.720
[Amit Varma]: another argument for another day, that's another argument for another day, we can agree to

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:58.180
[Amit Varma]: disagree and listeners can make up their own mind on that.

00:20:58.180 --> 00:21:02.400
[Amit Varma]: But all of this apart, I mean, what really struck me as a Ponzi element was that the

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:07.320
[Amit Varma]: fact that he is pledging his existing shares to buy more shares and then pledging those

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:12.120
[Amit Varma]: to you know, buy more shares and it's not really a scam because these are willing participants.

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:15.840
[Amit Varma]: I think Nomura is giving him the money Nomura is also funded by SoftBank.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:20.520
[Amit Varma]: Basically, this seems to be like SoftBank fooling itself, which they are entirely entitled

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest]: to do.

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And even if they were fooling others, these are, you know, open transactions, they're

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:26.840
[Amit Varma]: not actually lying about it.

00:21:26.840 --> 00:21:28.720
[Amit Varma]: So it is perfectly fine.

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:34.720
[Amit Varma]: However, Ponzi schemes typically in the way that we understand it outside of the structure

00:21:34.720 --> 00:21:40.840
[Amit Varma]: typically frauds, tell me a little bit more about, you know, you co wrote a paper in 2003,

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:44.400
[Amit Varma]: which I had the pleasure to read, you send it across to me.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:51.040
[Amit Varma]: And that had a whole bunch of sort of Indian examples of earlier Ponzi schemes.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:52.840
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about those.

00:21:52.840 --> 00:22:01.680
[Guest]: So, you know, it's, it's, I mean, Ponzi schemes have been in India for a very, very long time.

00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:06.200
[Guest]: And so I'll give you a few examples here.

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:13.240
[Guest]: So one of the earliest, you know, guys who sort of became famous for running Ponzi schemes

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:17.960
[Guest]: was actually an employee of, he was a bus conductor called Ashok Sheregar.

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:23.080
[Guest]: And he ran a number of Ponzi schemes in Mumbai, the famous ones being Vaibhavi Lakshmi, Money

00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:28.620
[Guest]: Circulation Scheme, Golden Chain, Dhan Varsha, Kuber and Diamond Circle.

00:22:28.620 --> 00:22:33.640
[Guest]: And what he used to do was obviously he promised a high rate of return and the initial investors

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:38.960
[Guest]: were appointed as agents with a promise of 2% commission on their investment.

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:43.600
[Guest]: And the commission was to be passed on when the agent brought in two or more investors.

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:46.240
[Guest]: So the new investors were again appointed as agents.

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:48.200
[Guest]: And so the cycle went on.

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:53.120
[Guest]: Now, obviously, Sheregar did not have a business model or anything in place.

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:58.760
[Guest]: He was just, you know, raising money and the money coming in from the latter investors

00:22:58.760 --> 00:23:02.280
[Guest]: was being used to pay off the former ones.

00:23:02.280 --> 00:23:07.800
[Guest]: And obviously, as long as the money coming in was more than the money going out, the

00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:10.400
[Guest]: schemes ran and then they collapsed.

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:18.160
[Guest]: Now, in case of Sheregar, you know, it was a blatant Ponzi scheme where he did not have

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:21.420
[Guest]: even a semblance of a business model in place.

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:24.320
[Guest]: But normally that is not the case.

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:31.380
[Guest]: You know, all Ponzi schemes have, not all, but a lot of Ponzi schemes have some sort

00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:35.560
[Guest]: of a business model in place, or at least they try to sort of show that they have a

00:23:35.560 --> 00:23:36.560
[Guest]: business model.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:41.440
[Amit Varma]: Even Charles Ponzi had that whole international reply coupons.

00:23:41.440 --> 00:23:46.120
[Guest]: So I don't know if you remember that, you know, in the 90s, there was this boom of plantation

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:47.120
[Guest]: companies.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:55.120
[Guest]: And the most famous of the lot was this one called Anubhav Plantations run by a gentleman

00:23:55.120 --> 00:23:57.120
[Guest]: called C. Natesan.

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:02.200
[Guest]: Now in one of his schemes for a deposit of rupees 6000, the investor was promised a piece

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:08.200
[Guest]: of land measuring 300 square feet, with three teak saplings planted on it.

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:12.360
[Guest]: Now, and this is a fairly elaborate, you know, business model.

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:16.600
[Guest]: For 20 years, Anubhav would be the caretaker of the land and the trees.

00:24:16.600 --> 00:24:20.780
[Guest]: In the first six years, the investor would get rupees 1000 back every year.

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:25.020
[Guest]: So at the end of, let's say, six years, his money that he had invested would already come

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:26.200
[Guest]: back to him.

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:31.880
[Guest]: And a 1000 rupee return on a 6000 rupee investment is pretty high.

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:38.160
[Guest]: I mean, it's almost 16-17% per year, I mean, that's not a bad return at all.

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:41.920
[Guest]: Added amounts of rupees 6000 and 12000 would be returned to the investor at the end of

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.640
[Guest]: the sixth year and the twelfth year.

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:49.000
[Guest]: When the scheme ended at the end of the 20th year, the investor got either rupees 3 lakhs

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.520
[Guest]: or 40 cubic feet of teak.

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:58.120
[Guest]: Now, the assumption was that each of the three teak trees would yield a volume of 1.13 cubic

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:02.520
[Guest]: meters and each cubic meter of wood would be sold at rupees 88,286.

00:25:02.520 --> 00:25:07.320
[Guest]: Now, I mean, this assumption was unrealistic and it never worked.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:11.040
[Guest]: And obviously, what Natesan was doing was he was taking the money being brought in by

00:25:11.040 --> 00:25:16.320
[Guest]: the older and newer investors and paying off the older investors.

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:21.800
[Guest]: So a lot of these schemes have a great, I mean, what looks like a business model in

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:22.880
[Guest]: place.

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:27.520
[Guest]: And this is something that has sort of, you know, gone on forever.

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:33.960
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at some of the newer Ponzi schemes also, you know, a few years back,

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:39.520
[Guest]: there was this scheme that came into light called the Stock Guru.

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:41.920
[Guest]: So Stock Guru had a very simple business model.

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:49.280
[Guest]: They promised returns as high as 20% per month on the basis of, you know, buying stocks at

00:25:49.280 --> 00:25:52.280
[Guest]: a low price and selling them at a high price.

00:25:52.280 --> 00:25:58.280
[Guest]: But 20% return per month, obviously not possible and not possible, I mean, it may be possible

00:25:58.280 --> 00:26:02.760
[Guest]: in an odd month here and there, but it's not something that you can guarantee.

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:07.120
[Guest]: Now, obviously, what they were doing was, you know, moving money.

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:13.000
[Guest]: And apparently, and, you know, after a point of time, the scheme collapsed.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:22.480
[Guest]: So yes, I mean, so most Ponzi schemes have a legitimate business model in place.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:23.480
[Guest]: Also, you know...

00:26:23.480 --> 00:26:26.400
[Guest]: As in they promise what appears to be a legitimate business model.

00:26:26.400 --> 00:26:31.020
[Guest]: Yeah, so it promises, it appears to be a genuine investment opportunity.

00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:36.520
[Guest]: So another great example here, and again, I mean, I'm using all these 90s examples,

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:40.840
[Guest]: because, you know, when I wrote the paper, you know, we had only the 90s examples, right?

00:26:40.840 --> 00:26:44.800
[Guest]: So this was written largely in, I think, 2002-2003.

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:50.000
[Guest]: So I don't know how many people would remember, in some time in the late 1990s, there was

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:56.120
[Guest]: this company called Home Trade, which advertised extensively.

00:26:56.120 --> 00:27:00.680
[Guest]: They had Hrithik Roshan, Sachin Tendulkar and Shah Rukh Khan.

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:05.520
[Guest]: I mean, maybe it was not even late 90s, it was probably early 2000s, because Kahona Pyaar

00:27:05.520 --> 00:27:08.880
[Guest]: Hai came only in the year 2000.

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:13.360
[Guest]: So anyway, the dates here are, I mean, we can all Google the dates.

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:17.440
[Guest]: So Home Trade essentially had a, again, you know, sort of a business model where they

00:27:17.440 --> 00:27:23.000
[Guest]: took money from cooperative banks, based in Maharashtra, and a provident fund called the

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:27.600
[Guest]: Seaman's Provident Fund for investing in short dated government securities.

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:31.160
[Guest]: So again, you know, some semblance of a business model.

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:35.080
[Guest]: The problem was, in most cases, no investment was made.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:41.400
[Guest]: And when the investment was made, these securities were pledged as collateral to raise more money.

00:27:41.400 --> 00:27:46.760
[Guest]: And the money would then be diverted into stock market financing, where higher returns

00:27:46.760 --> 00:27:49.520
[Guest]: could be earned, at least, you know, the hope was.

00:27:49.520 --> 00:27:54.520
[Guest]: Now, when a bank inquired about the securities, Home Trade would reply that the securities

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:55.920
[Guest]: had gone to RBI for clearance.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:59.560
[Guest]: I mean, during those days, things used to work manually.

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:03.560
[Guest]: And doing this, Home Trade bought itself time of around six to eight weeks.

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:09.000
[Guest]: On the date of maturity, you know, when the security had to be redeemed, Home Trade had

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:13.020
[Guest]: not invested, you know, or it had diverted money into the stock market.

00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:16.880
[Guest]: So what they would do is they would go to another cooperative bank, raise money from

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:20.720
[Guest]: them, and pay off the first one.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.080
[Guest]: And this is how the story went.

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:28.400
[Guest]: And, you know, and we used to sort of wonder as to, you know, what had Sachin and Hrithik

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:33.160
[Guest]: and Shah Rukh got to do with the entire, you know, company, because nobody really understood

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:37.920
[Guest]: at least in the public domain as to what, you know, the company actually did.

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:43.400
[Guest]: So it's just that these brand ambassadors provided that legitimacy to the company, you

00:28:43.400 --> 00:28:46.360
[Guest]: know, and then people went in.

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:49.960
[Guest]: So these ads were basically meant for all these cooperative banks to impress them.

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:52.640
[Guest]: Hey, boss, you know, we are paying these guys.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:55.320
[Guest]: So you know, you can lend us the money.

00:28:55.320 --> 00:29:03.360
[Guest]: I mean, so the point here is that a lot of Ponzi schemes have big brand ambassadors.

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:08.560
[Guest]: So the best example here is, and I mean, I hope both of us don't get sued, is that of

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:09.560
[Guest]: Sahara.

00:29:09.560 --> 00:29:15.160
[Guest]: Sahara used the Indian cricket team as their brand ambassador, I mean, for a very, very

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:16.160
[Guest]: long time.

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:19.200
[Guest]: I mean, they also sponsored the hockey team.

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:25.560
[Guest]: Now, obviously, when a normal guy who is depositing money with Sahara, I mean, whatever, you know,

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:30.320
[Guest]: the 50 rupees or the 100 rupees or whatever he, you know, deposits daily, he looks at

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:34.360
[Guest]: the fact that these guys are sponsoring the Indian cricket team.

00:29:34.360 --> 00:29:39.320
[Guest]: I mean, there is no bigger brand in India than the Indian cricket team, right, at least

00:29:39.320 --> 00:29:41.320
[Guest]: much through the 90s and the early 2000s.

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:47.560
[Guest]: I mean, now we can debate because there are badminton stars and yeah, but I like cricketers

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.720
[Amit Varma]: are still the biggest guys, right?

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:55.240
[Guest]: So when you have the cricket team, sort of wearing the logo, wearing a company's logo,

00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:59.880
[Guest]: obviously, people, you know, will give it money very, very easily.

00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:06.200
[Guest]: Now, the problem was, Sahara also was in multiple businesses all over the place.

00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:10.360
[Guest]: But you know, whether these businesses were making money, no one really knew.

00:30:10.360 --> 00:30:12.760
[Guest]: The core business was chit funds, basically.

00:30:12.760 --> 00:30:16.640
[Guest]: But it wasn't, I mean, once upon a time, that is how they started.

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:17.640
[Guest]: What are chit funds?

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:18.640
[Guest]: Are they Ponzi schemes?

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:19.640
[Guest]: No, they're not.

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:20.880
[Guest]: So I'll explain what are chit funds.

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:24.800
[Guest]: So chit funds are essentially, you know, you know, what kitty parties are, right?

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:25.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:28.200
[Guest]: Okay, so they're basically kitty parties with a twist.

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:29.200
[Guest]: Okay.

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:34.240
[Guest]: Now, what happens in a kitty party is that, you know, women come together, and they contribute

00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:37.400
[Guest]: a given amount of money every month.

00:30:37.400 --> 00:30:46.640
[Guest]: And then a chit is sort of, you know, selected, and, you know, the name, you know, who are

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:51.560
[Guest]: the woman is whose name is on the on the chit gets all the money contributed in that month.

00:30:51.560 --> 00:31:00.040
[Guest]: So let's say, there are 12 women, and they get 10 bucks each, 5000, 10 bucks, an illustration

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:08.360
[Guest]: of example, so there are, let's say, 12 women, and they give a lakh each 5000, 5000, so 5000,

00:31:08.360 --> 00:31:10.120
[Guest]: and they meet once a month.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:15.520
[Guest]: So when they pool the money together, it works out to a total of 60,000 rupees, 12 names

00:31:15.520 --> 00:31:20.440
[Guest]: are written on a chit on sheets of paper from these chits, one chit is drawn, and the woman

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:22.880
[Guest]: whose name is on the chit gets the rupees 60,000.

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:24.400
[Guest]: Okay, as simple as that.

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:29.160
[Guest]: Now, when they meet next month, 11 months, 11 names are written on the chits, one name

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:35.040
[Guest]: is drawn, and that woman gets the money, then when they meet again, then 10 names are written,

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:36.040
[Guest]: and so the cycle works.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:40.400
[Guest]: So, so eventually, you know, there is one woman left who in the last month gets the

00:31:40.400 --> 00:31:41.800
[Guest]: 60,000 rupees.

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:48.000
[Guest]: So basically, what is happening here is that, you know, every month by putting in 5000 rupees

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:53.440
[Guest]: every month, you get 60,000 bucks at one go, and you can then do something substantial

00:31:53.440 --> 00:31:54.440
[Guest]: with it, right?

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:58.640
[Guest]: Now, of course, the problem here is that, you know, some women might drop out, some

00:31:58.640 --> 00:32:00.400
[Guest]: may not be able to pay.

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:03.320
[Guest]: So someone who's already got the money may not pay.

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:06.880
[Guest]: So I mean, there's nothing, you know, that stops people from doing it.

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:10.480
[Guest]: Now, a chit fund actually works slightly differently.

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:16.320
[Guest]: Now, again, let's assume that there are 12 women, and they contribute 5000.

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:21.440
[Guest]: So this means a total of 60,000 has been collected every month.

00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:27.880
[Guest]: Then what happens is that the amount that is collected is auctioned to the 12 members

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:30.280
[Guest]: after a minimum discount has been set.

00:32:30.280 --> 00:32:31.640
[Guest]: Now, what does that mean?

00:32:31.640 --> 00:32:34.640
[Guest]: So let's say the minimum discount is 5000 rupees.

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:39.920
[Guest]: This means that the maximum amount any woman can get from the total rupees 60,000 collected

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:42.840
[Guest]: is rupees 55,000, okay?

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:45.760
[Guest]: After these discount bids are invited, all the women bid.

00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:49.380
[Guest]: Now, let's say one woman bids a discount of rupees 12,000.

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:54.040
[Guest]: So this is the highest discount that has been bid and hence she gets the money.

00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:58.320
[Guest]: So since the agreed on discount is 12,000, she would get rupees 48,000.

00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:02.520
[Guest]: But then there are some, you know, other organizing charges, etc, etc.

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:06.040
[Guest]: So typically, she would get something like a 45,000 rupees.

00:33:06.040 --> 00:33:14.500
[Guest]: Okay, now, the discount of 12,000 is basically the profit that the group as a whole has made.

00:33:14.500 --> 00:33:18.320
[Guest]: And then it's divided, you know, 12,000 divided by 12.

00:33:18.320 --> 00:33:21.480
[Guest]: So 1000 rupees goes to every member.

00:33:21.480 --> 00:33:28.200
[Guest]: So now, of course, the woman who got the 45,000 rupees will now keep contributing, you know,

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:33.280
[Guest]: 5000 rupees every month for the remaining 11 months and in every month, there will be

00:33:33.280 --> 00:33:40.840
[Guest]: a sort of an auction and the woman who sort of offers the maximum discount will get the

00:33:40.840 --> 00:33:41.840
[Guest]: money.

00:33:41.840 --> 00:33:44.800
[Guest]: So this is how a chit fund is supposed to work.

00:33:44.800 --> 00:33:46.880
[Guest]: So chit funds are not Ponzi schemes.

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:54.720
[Guest]: But what happens is, a lot of people who because chit funds are in the imagination of people.

00:33:54.720 --> 00:34:00.920
[Guest]: So a lot of people who run Ponzi schemes, call their investment schemes as chit funds.

00:34:00.920 --> 00:34:04.240
[Guest]: So which is why chit funds have got a bad name.

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:10.480
[Guest]: I mean, if you look at a state like, you know, what used to be erstwhile Andhra Pradesh and

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:16.120
[Guest]: now is Telangana and Andhra Pradesh, there are lots of big chit funds that are run in

00:34:16.120 --> 00:34:19.040
[Guest]: that state and they have been around for a while now.

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:25.120
[Guest]: So in a way, you know, a lot of Ponzi schemes have spoiled the, the name of chit funds.

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:28.440
[Guest]: So, so it's not all chit funds are not Ponzi schemes.

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:32.640
[Guest]: But Ponzi schemes are run in the name of running a chit fund very often.

00:34:32.640 --> 00:34:33.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:37.440
[Guest]: And so chit funds are basically kitty parties, which gives us a great promotional code for

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:41.340
[Guest]: the quote for the episode.

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:45.080
[Amit Varma]: What also interests me is the point noting like while prepping for this episode, I read

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:49.720
[Amit Varma]: this biography of Charles Ponzi called Ponzi scheme by Mitchell Zukov, which you also read.

00:34:49.720 --> 00:34:54.920
[Amit Varma]: And excellent book, which I would recommend and which also has one interesting element

00:34:54.920 --> 00:35:00.080
[Amit Varma]: of every Ponzi scheme, which is that once people get there, once the first batch of

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:03.680
[Amit Varma]: investors when they get their interest for the first time, number one, what they tend

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:08.360
[Amit Varma]: to do is they tend to reinvest it immediately, because they are obviously greedy.

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:11.920
[Amit Varma]: So you don't even have to pay out the entire batch of first investors.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, once they actually get the money, like you've put 100 bucks and got 150 bucks

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:21.000
[Amit Varma]: in 45 days, you become a hardcore evangelist for the company, you tell all your friends,

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.760
[Amit Varma]: you tell your relatives, you sell your house and put that money in.

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:29.480
[Amit Varma]: And it's just one thing upon another, which is, you know, and towards the end of this

00:35:29.480 --> 00:35:35.680
[Amit Varma]: episode, we'll kind of discuss human nature also and why we as a species are particularly

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:37.720
[Amit Varma]: prone to such frauds.

00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:42.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, other animals eat, you know, the fellow members of the species, but they don't cheat

00:35:42.680 --> 00:35:44.080
[Amit Varma]: them in this way.

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And one angle I'd also like you to expand upon is a multilevel marketing, the MLM angle.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:54.440
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, one of the things that you mentioned, which was true of Ponzi also,

00:35:54.440 --> 00:35:58.820
[Amit Varma]: which is true of say, Sharagar, what you were saying, is that he turned his early investors

00:35:58.820 --> 00:36:00.640
[Guest]: into agents.

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:03.960
[Amit Varma]: And then those agents got a commission, and they had more sub agents.

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And that sounds very much to me like a multilevel marketing.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:11.000
[Guest]: So multilevel marketing now, in case of Ashok Sharagar, he was just getting agents.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:15.960
[Guest]: Now, if let's say he had a product attached to the entire thing, let's say, you know,

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:20.420
[Guest]: every agent had to sell a bar of soap for 100 bucks, something, you know, some special

00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:21.420
[Guest]: bar of soap.

00:36:21.420 --> 00:36:24.880
[Guest]: Now, that would have given him a legitimate purpose, right?

00:36:24.880 --> 00:36:29.700
[Guest]: So if you look at a lot of multilevel marketing schemes, I mean, even though they sort of

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:35.720
[Guest]: come attached with a product which needs to be sold, the money actually is made in getting

00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:39.000
[Guest]: more and more members.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:46.520
[Guest]: Even those, you know, if you look at even, you know, I mean, legitimate MLM schemes,

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:50.800
[Guest]: you know, the money is basically made by getting more and more members and then selling them

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:52.600
[Guest]: those products, right?

00:36:52.600 --> 00:37:03.160
[Guest]: Now, the problem here is that if you do not enter the MLM scheme at a higher level, and

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:09.200
[Guest]: if you enter it at a lower level, I mean, by then it's too late to make any money irrespective

00:37:09.200 --> 00:37:13.560
[Guest]: of whether you're in a legitimate scheme or you're in an illegitimate scheme.

00:37:13.560 --> 00:37:20.200
[Guest]: Now, you know, if you're in an illegitimate MLM, if you're in what is an outer Ponzi scheme,

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:25.200
[Guest]: I mean, you need to take into account the level that you're entering it at, but then

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:26.200
[Guest]: how do you figure that out?

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:28.880
[Guest]: There is no way of doing that, right?

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:35.640
[Guest]: So the point I'm trying to make here is that if a Ponzi scheme becomes too big, it collapses

00:37:35.640 --> 00:37:37.880
[Guest]: under its own weight, okay?

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:41.800
[Guest]: So let me just give you a very simple example here.

00:37:41.800 --> 00:37:45.280
[Guest]: Let's say someone starts a Ponzi scheme, okay?

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:51.040
[Guest]: He gets 100 members and each member is supposed to contribute 10,000 rupees and is promised

00:37:51.040 --> 00:37:54.840
[Guest]: a return of 50,000 rupees at the end of one year, okay?

00:37:54.840 --> 00:38:01.840
[Guest]: Now, if every investor who's promised, I mean, if the guy sort of doesn't want to run away

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:07.120
[Guest]: with the money at the very beginning and wants to sort of be in business at the end of one

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:08.120
[Guest]: year.

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:15.920
[Guest]: So every investor who's paid 10,000 needs to be paid 50,000 rupees, okay?

00:38:15.920 --> 00:38:21.280
[Guest]: Now so for every investor who has to be paid off, the guy needs five new investors to come

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:22.280
[Guest]: in.

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:26.160
[Guest]: So for five new investors, he needs 500 investors, okay?

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:28.960
[Guest]: Because then the money will balance itself out.

00:38:28.960 --> 00:38:32.960
[Guest]: Now let's say at the end of second year, he wants to continue going again.

00:38:32.960 --> 00:38:37.960
[Guest]: So for 500 investors, he needs 2,500 investors.

00:38:37.960 --> 00:38:40.600
[Guest]: Then for 2,500, he needs 12,500.

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:47.160
[Guest]: Now by the time you reach the ninth level, the number goes up to something like 19.6

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:50.000
[Guest]: crore or some very big number, right?

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:54.800
[Guest]: So that is not, I mean, you know, to get so many people involved is simply not possible.

00:38:54.800 --> 00:39:00.440
[Guest]: So which is why, you know, eventually all Ponzi schemes collapse under their own weight.

00:39:00.440 --> 00:39:05.360
[Guest]: And which is why even in an MLM scheme, if you are even in a legitimate MLM scheme, where

00:39:05.360 --> 00:39:10.400
[Guest]: you actually make money by selling products, if you're entering it like too late, there

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:14.680
[Guest]: is no way you can, you can only buy products beyond a point everyone else around you would

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:20.720
[Guest]: already be an agent, and they would already be buying products of the company, which is

00:39:20.720 --> 00:39:25.640
[Guest]: something which happened to Amway in a very big way, you know, people who entered it in

00:39:25.640 --> 00:39:29.400
[Guest]: the early stages made a lot of money, but by, you know, by the time it actually picked

00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:34.840
[Guest]: up and the general janta got in, you know, you had some five Amway agents.

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:40.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, both of us are old enough to remember a time where, you know, the biggest pest in

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:46.320
[Guest]: your social circle was the Amway agent, because he would be freaking desperate, because he's

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:50.360
[Amit Varma]: at the bottom of the scale, he has no way of making money, he's invested tons of money

00:39:50.360 --> 00:39:51.760
[Amit Varma]: into this shit.

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's like you meet them in parties, you meet them at kitty parties.

00:39:55.440 --> 00:39:58.520
[Guest]: I mean, they used to have these parties, they used to organize kitty parties too.

00:39:58.520 --> 00:40:03.840
[Guest]: In fact, the other point that you know, talking of Amway, it reminds me, so if you look at

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:09.180
[Guest]: these MLM companies, I mean, legitimate and illegitimate, they organize these meetings

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:14.920
[Guest]: where they get their star, sort of, you know, early investors who've made a lot of money,

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:18.360
[Guest]: and then these guys come and give these motivational talks.

00:40:18.360 --> 00:40:22.740
[Guest]: And you know, then everyone starts to feel no, you know, we can also do it.

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:26.980
[Guest]: But then it's not about, you know, there was nothing that they did, they just happened

00:40:26.980 --> 00:40:31.560
[Guest]: to be at the right place, at the right time and entered the scheme at the right level.

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:34.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it was as simple as that, you know, and they might even drink their own Koolaid

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:38.160
[Amit Varma]: and they might even think this is a fantastic idea and that they've made so much money like

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:42.520
[Amit Varma]: one of the interesting things I learned about Charles Ponzi was that at one point in time,

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:47.280
[Amit Varma]: he had $7 million in the bank, and he could just have taken his family and gone back to

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:48.280
[Amit Varma]: Italy.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:49.280
[Amit Varma]: He wasn't even an American citizen.

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:53.400
[Amit Varma]: He was still an Italian citizen and could just have left and gone back to Italy.

00:40:53.400 --> 00:40:58.040
[Amit Varma]: But he stayed on because he was actually of the belief that he would come out of this

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:00.360
[Guest]: okay at the end, he managed to convince himself.

00:41:00.360 --> 00:41:06.080
[Guest]: So he had, I mean, the number that I remember writing in the paper, he had 40,000 investors

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:10.280
[Guest]: who had invested $15 million at the peak of the scheme.

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the figure that I've read somewhere is at the peak, it was about 20 million, which

00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:18.720
[Amit Varma]: would be 250 in current terms, but whatever it was, it was a ton of money and and a lot

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:22.800
[Amit Varma]: of it actually went into paying back the earlier investors and all that.

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:27.600
[Amit Varma]: But at one point in time, he had 7 million free lying around and he could just have fled

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:28.960
[Amit Varma]: and he chose not to flee.

00:41:28.960 --> 00:41:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And eventually, of course, he spent two jail terms of five years and I think seven to nine

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:38.240
[Amit Varma]: years respectively, and then he was deported because he wasn't an American citizen.

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:44.760
[Guest]: And he died alone in a welfare hospital in Rio de Janeiro of all places in 1944 or something

00:41:44.760 --> 00:41:46.120
[Guest]: 4949.

00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:50.080
[Amit Varma]: And his wife also left him in all this and lived to a ripe old age.

00:41:50.080 --> 00:41:52.640
[Guest]: In fact, he tried running more Ponzi schemes later in his life.

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:53.640
[Amit Varma]: Oh, really?

00:41:53.640 --> 00:41:54.640
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:55.640
[Guest]: I didn't read about that.

00:41:55.640 --> 00:42:00.160
[Guest]: I mean, something to do with land in Florida, from what I remember reading, yeah, that that

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:04.280
[Amit Varma]: was in fact, after his first jail term, when he came out before the second jail term, he

00:42:04.280 --> 00:42:07.960
[Amit Varma]: tried to do something with land in Florida, which again fell apart because he couldn't

00:42:07.960 --> 00:42:08.960
[Amit Varma]: raise funds.

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, it might actually have worked.

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:16.320
[Amit Varma]: But it's not unlikely that a man with so many jail sentences before is unable, which is

00:42:16.320 --> 00:42:17.800
[Guest]: why he went from Boston to Florida.

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:19.480
[Unknown]: I mean, those days.

00:42:19.480 --> 00:42:23.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it wasn't, you know, like separate countries are mostly, mostly like separate

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:24.800
[Amit Varma]: countries.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:27.040
[Amit Varma]: So fascinating stuff.

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:33.200
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, Ponzi schemes is not just something that happens at the unsophisticated

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:38.880
[Amit Varma]: level of housewives who are buying Amway products or whatever, they're very sophisticated.

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And we've seen this.

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:41.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they continue to the present day.

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:46.680
[Amit Varma]: And we've seen this most recently in the case of the multi billion dollar Ponzi scheme run

00:42:46.680 --> 00:42:47.680
[Amit Varma]: by Bernie Madoff.

00:42:47.680 --> 00:42:48.960
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:57.320
[Guest]: So Bernie Madoff was this guy who, you know, every rich American wanted to invest with,

00:42:57.320 --> 00:43:04.400
[Guest]: because he gave stable returns, he never lost money, and he was Jewish.

00:43:04.400 --> 00:43:10.120
[Guest]: So that that helps now, but what he was doing all along was basically rotating money.

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:15.980
[Guest]: And when the financial crisis stuck, it just became very, very difficult to continue rotating

00:43:15.980 --> 00:43:20.880
[Guest]: money because prices of everything sort of fell.

00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:25.060
[Guest]: But even then, his scheme sort of showed a positive rate of return, you know, when everything

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:30.000
[Guest]: else was crashing and hedge funds were sort of shutting down a dozen.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:36.120
[Guest]: And but ultimately, you know, he just got fed up of it and, and, you know, went and

00:43:36.120 --> 00:43:41.320
[Guest]: told the authorities that this is what I've been up to and, you know, and obviously, you

00:43:41.320 --> 00:43:45.360
[Guest]: know, justice got done and he was put in jail and so on and so forth.

00:43:45.360 --> 00:43:50.840
[Guest]: But the interesting thing here is that, you know, no one caught on to it for so many years,

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:56.160
[Guest]: it was, you know, if he had, if he had managed to sort of write that brief period when the

00:43:56.160 --> 00:44:01.080
[Guest]: financial crisis stuck, he would probably have continued, you know, even now.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:06.600
[Amit Varma]: So there's a very nice book called Anatomy of a Ponzi scheme by Colleen Cross.

00:44:06.600 --> 00:44:10.600
[Amit Varma]: And in that she looks at a whole bunch of Ponzi schemes.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:15.040
[Amit Varma]: And if I remember correctly, half of the biggest 10 of all time, fell apart because of the

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:16.040
[Amit Varma]: 2008 crisis.

00:44:16.040 --> 00:44:20.880
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, like Madoff scheme, no one had, which is the biggest, I think, at about 65

00:44:20.880 --> 00:44:21.880
[Amit Varma]: billion.

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:26.120
[Amit Varma]: No one had actually noticed this was a Ponzi scheme, it was a respected investment fund

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:29.960
[Amit Varma]: or hedge fund in different cases, and you kind of put your money there, they're giving

00:44:29.960 --> 00:44:33.600
[Amit Varma]: you stable returns, it seems to be, you know, they just seem to be good investors, nothing

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:34.600
[Amit Varma]: else.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:39.160
[Amit Varma]: But the 2008 crisis meant that, you know, there was a liquidity crunch among investors,

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:41.880
[Amit Varma]: too many investors asked to take their money back.

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:47.360
[Guest]: And, you know, the scam fell apart just out of the country running it.

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:54.640
[Guest]: So yeah, which is so even even closer to home, I mean, I mean, they were West Bengal in the

00:44:54.640 --> 00:44:58.240
[Guest]: last decade has had their fair share of Ponzi schemes.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:04.120
[Guest]: And I remember one of my father's friends, you know, called when when when when I think

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:08.560
[Guest]: Sarada was the scheme which went bust, he called up and said, Hey, you know, I lost

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:09.560
[Guest]: so much money.

00:45:09.560 --> 00:45:14.640
[Guest]: And it's not like, you know, only the uneducated lot, even the educated lot puts money into

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:17.320
[Guest]: these schemes, and then they lose.

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:23.680
[Guest]: So in fact, the Sarada case is also very interesting that they really cashed in on the celebrity

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:29.880
[Guest]: part of the Ponzi scheme to make themselves, you know, sound legitimate.

00:45:29.880 --> 00:45:33.520
[Guest]: So I just like to sort of read out something here.

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:41.440
[Guest]: So Sarada, you know, was run by a gentleman called Sudipta Sen, okay, Sudipta Sen, Sudipta

00:45:41.440 --> 00:45:42.440
[Guest]: Sen.

00:45:42.440 --> 00:45:49.240
[Guest]: Okay, if you were to pronounce it in the proper Bengali way, Sudipta Sen, okay.

00:45:49.240 --> 00:45:53.440
[Guest]: So Sudipta Sen ensured that the Sarada group had huge presence in the media.

00:45:53.440 --> 00:45:58.200
[Guest]: I'm quoting the business standard here, which says his first entry into the space was through

00:45:58.200 --> 00:45:59.440
[Guest]: Channel 10.

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:04.360
[Guest]: And thereafter, he expanded into Dailies, The Bengal Post, if you remember that newspaper,

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:07.880
[Guest]: and Sakaalvela, which obviously means the afternoon.

00:46:07.880 --> 00:46:11.040
[Guest]: In 2010, Sen bought out Tara Channels as well.

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:15.580
[Guest]: At the time of closing down, the group had 10 media outfits, news TV channels, newspapers

00:46:15.580 --> 00:46:16.580
[Guest]: and magazines.

00:46:16.580 --> 00:46:20.600
[Guest]: Now, this gave a lot of credibility and helped building the brand.

00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:27.080
[Guest]: The cine actor Mithun Chakraborty was the brand ambassador for Channel 10.

00:46:27.080 --> 00:46:30.800
[Guest]: The Trinamool party was also seen being close to the group.

00:46:30.800 --> 00:46:37.440
[Guest]: Now, this is again a Sarada agent called Reba Mitra, you know, telling NDTV.com when the

00:46:37.440 --> 00:46:39.760
[Guest]: scam sort of came to the fore.

00:46:39.760 --> 00:46:44.680
[Guest]: We put our faith in Sarada because big leaders of the Trinamool like Madan Mitra, Didi, the

00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:52.120
[Guest]: Chief Minister, Kunal Ghosh, Shatabdi Roy, Mithun Chakraborty, when these big people

00:46:52.120 --> 00:47:06.880
[Guest]: are with them, government people, then would this money be stolen from us?

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:14.000
[Guest]: Now, I mean, this is a very, you know, this is how the entire scheme got its legitimacy.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:20.120
[Guest]: And you know, the interesting thing is the, the kind of returns that all these schemes,

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:21.120
[Guest]: you know, offer.

00:47:21.120 --> 00:47:28.480
[Guest]: Sarada was offering returns of anywhere between 17.5 to 22%, so, which is something that sort

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:33.240
[Guest]: of, you know, attracted a lot of people to, you know, put money there.

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:36.720
[Guest]: You know, another interesting scheme that, you know, I would like to talk about, and

00:47:36.720 --> 00:47:40.800
[Guest]: this is also a recent one, is called PACL.

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:41.800
[Guest]: Okay.

00:47:41.800 --> 00:47:48.240
[Guest]: Now, this was big in and around, you know, Delhi and North India until, you know, the

00:47:48.240 --> 00:47:53.000
[Guest]: Securities Exchange Board of India cracked down on it, and the scheme had managed to

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:57.440
[Guest]: sort of, you know, raise as much as 50,000 crore from people.

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:02.920
[Guest]: Now, they also had, you know, their business model was very interesting, so-called, not

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:06.640
[Guest]: the, I mean, there was no business model actually.

00:48:06.640 --> 00:48:12.840
[Guest]: So it told people that they were actually buying rights to a plot of land when they

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:14.480
[Guest]: deposited money with the company.

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:19.440
[Guest]: Now, when they wanted the money back, the company would sell the land, but apart from

00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:23.880
[Guest]: this underlying fiction, it worked very much like you could walk in and deposit money for

00:48:23.880 --> 00:48:24.880
[Unknown]: a high return.

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:25.880
[Guest]: Okay.

00:48:25.880 --> 00:48:30.120
[Guest]: Now, obviously, there was, you know, they were not selling and buying land and all that,

00:48:30.120 --> 00:48:32.760
[Guest]: they were just rotating money.

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:37.440
[Guest]: So this was one of the, you know, the biggest Ponzi schemes in recent times.

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:43.480
[Guest]: And what happens is, you know, when these fraudsters get caught, you hear a lot of news

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:45.240
[Guest]: and then everything fizzles out.

00:48:45.240 --> 00:48:49.200
[Guest]: So we never really come to know as to whether these guys were convicted, what happened to

00:48:49.200 --> 00:48:50.200
[Guest]: them?

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:51.440
[Guest]: Did people get their money back?

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:56.400
[Guest]: I mean, all this news never reaches us.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:00.580
[Guest]: And these schemes, you know, continue in one avatar or the other, I mean, there was one

00:49:00.580 --> 00:49:09.800
[Guest]: in Bangalore, which recently sort of, you know, came out, that was also associated with

00:49:09.800 --> 00:49:10.800
[Amit Varma]: real estate.

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:15.320
[Amit Varma]: No, in abroad, I think the standards is that when Ponzi schemes get uncovered, then all

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:21.400
[Amit Varma]: of those early investors, they have to give up that whatever return that they got on it,

00:49:21.400 --> 00:49:23.120
[Amit Varma]: and that goes into a central pool.

00:49:23.120 --> 00:49:28.520
[Amit Varma]: And then the overall pool of investors are paid from that in a pro rata way.

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:32.560
[Amit Varma]: So you do actually end up getting some of your money back, like in the original, like

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:39.280
[Amit Varma]: in the Charles Ponzi scheme, for example, I think people got about 27 out of every hundred

00:49:39.280 --> 00:49:47.760
[Amit Varma]: dollars I haven't heard of anything in India, of course, in what's also interesting in India

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:54.000
[Amit Varma]: is that all the examples we've discussed are Ponzi schemes done by private parties, where

00:49:54.000 --> 00:50:00.440
[Amit Varma]: it is willing individuals who even if they are fooled, at least voluntarily part with

00:50:00.440 --> 00:50:05.580
[Amit Varma]: their hard earned money, even if they're fooled on false premises, and obviously the organizers

00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:07.800
[Amit Varma]: of those fraud should go to jail.

00:50:07.800 --> 00:50:13.200
[Amit Varma]: But after the break, we are going to talk about government run Ponzi schemes, which

00:50:13.200 --> 00:50:19.800
[Amit Varma]: are run at a far larger scale, and aware of the people who are actually losing money,

00:50:19.800 --> 00:50:22.480
[Amit Varma]: have that money taken from them without their consent.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:24.800
[Amit Varma]: And in some cases, they aren't even born yet.

