[Amit Varma]: one of his favorite subjects, Ponzi schemes. And I said before the break that we'll talk

00:52:24.460 --> 00:52:29.820
[Amit Varma]: about Ponzi schemes run by the government of which we are the unwilling victims. But

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:36.020
[Amit Varma]: before we do that, Vivek has some other entertaining examples of private Ponzi schemes, which he

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:37.420
[Amit Varma]: would like to tell us about.

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:44.300
[Guest]: Okay, so you know, one of the in the state of Tamil Nadu, some enterprising entrepreneurs

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:50.180
[Guest]: ran a Ponzi scheme around the emu bird, where, you know, you invest money and this entrepreneur

00:52:50.180 --> 00:52:55.140
[Guest]: would rear these birds and when they were sufficiently big, he would sell meat, their

00:52:55.140 --> 00:52:56.140
[Guest]: oil etc.

00:52:56.140 --> 00:52:59.900
[Guest]: He'd give you, you know, whatever money that you're interested in.

00:52:59.900 --> 00:53:00.900
[Guest]: Ponzi scheme around cows.

00:53:00.900 --> 00:53:05.740
[Guest]: Don't go there. So, so this was one interesting scheme that I remember. Another interesting

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:13.980
[Guest]: scheme was something called Speak Asia. I mean, a lot of people would remember it. Now,

00:53:13.980 --> 00:53:18.460
[Guest]: so basically, Speak Asia had a very, again, it had a business model. And the model was

00:53:18.460 --> 00:53:24.180
[Guest]: that in order to become a member of Speak Asia, you had to invest 11,000 rupees. The

00:53:24.180 --> 00:53:29.060
[Guest]: investment was for subscribing to the electronic magazine issued by the company called Surveys

00:53:29.060 --> 00:53:30.060
[Guest]: Today.

00:53:30.060 --> 00:53:36.020
[Guest]: Now, this allowed the member to participate in two online surveys every week and make

00:53:36.020 --> 00:53:41.380
[Guest]: rupees 500 per survey or rupees 1000 per week. This when converted into an yearly number

00:53:41.380 --> 00:53:47.100
[Guest]: came to 52,000 rupees. So the an investment of 11,000 rupees gave you 52,000 at the end

00:53:47.100 --> 00:53:54.580
[Guest]: of the year. So which is a return of 373% in one year, not bad at all. Now, obviously,

00:53:54.580 --> 00:53:59.100
[Guest]: you know, there were no surveys or even if they were, they were, they were not as many

00:53:59.100 --> 00:54:04.540
[Guest]: as were required to sort of generate the return that the company had promised. So ultimately,

00:54:04.540 --> 00:54:08.820
[Guest]: the scheme collapsed. Now, in my particular case, you know, the reason I remember this

00:54:08.820 --> 00:54:14.620
[Guest]: very well is that at that particular point of time, I used to work for a weekly personal

00:54:14.620 --> 00:54:20.340
[Guest]: finance newspaper. And Speak Asia had a half page ad in it. So you know, imagine a Ponzi

00:54:20.340 --> 00:54:25.180
[Guest]: scheme being advertised in a personal finance newspaper. I mean, Speak Asia had ads all

00:54:25.180 --> 00:54:31.460
[Guest]: over the place. Yeah, it wasn't just just that, just that newspaper, the ads were published

00:54:31.460 --> 00:54:38.420
[Guest]: in but including that newspaper. So another interesting scheme that I remember is is was

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:45.700
[Guest]: a Russian Ponzi scheme called MMM, which finally came to India as well. And they you know,

00:54:45.700 --> 00:54:52.060
[Guest]: where they were the most blatant of the lot in the sense that they offered to grow an

00:54:52.060 --> 00:54:59.580
[Guest]: initial investment of rupees 5000 to rupees 3.4 crore at the end of I mean, and there

00:54:59.580 --> 00:55:04.740
[Guest]: were some and when I wrote pieces against that Ponzi scheme, there were people who got

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:10.100
[Guest]: back to me in order to tell me that, you know, I didn't understand the business model. So

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:14.460
[Guest]: it happens every time, you know, this is a standard response when you write on a Ponzi

00:55:14.460 --> 00:55:19.340
[Guest]: scheme, people write back to you that, you know, you don't know anything about this.

00:55:19.340 --> 00:55:27.180
[Guest]: So you should shut up and keep your theory with you, because we are actually making money.

00:55:27.180 --> 00:55:31.900
[Guest]: And that's the best part, you know, as we discussed, the initial guys always make money

00:55:31.900 --> 00:55:36.620
[Guest]: and then they become, you know, evangelists for the company and go around telling people

00:55:36.620 --> 00:55:41.140
[Guest]: that boss, I have made money, this is safe. And you know, you can also invest in it.

00:55:41.140 --> 00:55:45.180
[Amit Varma]: But in this case, who's going to put 5000 and actually make 3 point whatever crores

00:55:45.180 --> 00:55:48.100
[Unknown]: at the end of the year, how many more suckers do you need for that?

00:55:48.100 --> 00:55:51.980
[Guest]: People did fall for it initially.

00:55:51.980 --> 00:55:55.300
[Amit Varma]: In the case of the government, of course, there's no falling for it, because we are

00:55:55.300 --> 00:56:03.540
[Amit Varma]: willy nilly entrapped into it by way of being taxpayers and which matter, we do not have

00:56:03.540 --> 00:56:04.540
[Amit Varma]: a choice.

00:56:04.540 --> 00:56:08.220
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit like, you know, earlier before this, when we were having breakfast at the

00:56:08.220 --> 00:56:12.460
[Amit Varma]: most excellent car social, we had Sid's very posh breakfast with ham and cheese omelette.

00:56:12.460 --> 00:56:16.500
[Amit Varma]: And over there, you when I mentioned to you that, when I was speaking about how America's

00:56:16.500 --> 00:56:21.820
[Amit Varma]: social security is a Ponzi scheme, you said why India's also expand a bit.

00:56:21.820 --> 00:56:29.180
[Guest]: So basically, you know, if many of us invest in small savings schemes run by the post office,

00:56:29.180 --> 00:56:35.220
[Guest]: this includes everything from, you know, the post office accounts to post office monthly

00:56:35.220 --> 00:56:39.660
[Guest]: income scheme to public provident fund and so on so forth.

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:43.180
[Guest]: Now, the way it works is very, very interesting.

00:56:43.180 --> 00:56:49.860
[Guest]: So all this money essentially is collected, and it comes under the National Small Savings

00:56:49.860 --> 00:56:51.980
[Guest]: Fund.

00:56:51.980 --> 00:56:59.380
[Guest]: And what happens is, so let's say, in a given year, 1,50,000 crore is the money coming into

00:56:59.380 --> 00:57:00.380
[Guest]: these schemes.

00:57:00.380 --> 00:57:01.380
[Guest]: Okay.

00:57:01.380 --> 00:57:07.940
[Guest]: And in that year, if 50,000 crore is to be redeemed, then 50,000 crore is taken from

00:57:07.940 --> 00:57:11.280
[Guest]: that 1,50,000 crore and redeemed.

00:57:11.280 --> 00:57:17.940
[Guest]: And the remaining 1,00,000 crore is a revenue in the annual budget of the Indian government.

00:57:17.940 --> 00:57:18.940
[Guest]: Okay.

00:57:18.940 --> 00:57:25.420
[Guest]: So, so what is happening here is as long as the money that keeps coming into these schemes

00:57:25.420 --> 00:57:30.900
[Guest]: is higher than the money that needs to be paid off to the investors whose investment

00:57:30.900 --> 00:57:35.220
[Guest]: is maturing, you know, the scheme will keep running.

00:57:35.220 --> 00:57:43.300
[Guest]: So it has a structure of a Ponzi scheme wherein new money is being used to pay off the investment

00:57:43.300 --> 00:57:44.940
[Amit Varma]: that is being redeemed.

00:57:44.940 --> 00:57:49.060
[Amit Varma]: My impression was that whatever you sort of deposit is invested by them into something

00:57:49.060 --> 00:57:52.020
[Amit Varma]: else and they get a rate of return there and that is a basis.

00:57:52.020 --> 00:57:57.220
[Guest]: No, so what happens is the money is first repaid and then the remaining money, the National

00:57:57.220 --> 00:58:01.300
[Guest]: Small Savings Fund is invested into various things.

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:06.460
[Guest]: But then what if you know what it is invested in, you will not, you know, it will screw

00:58:06.460 --> 00:58:08.740
[Guest]: you up even further.

00:58:08.740 --> 00:58:14.620
[Guest]: So the NSS of money right now, a lot of it is has been lent to the Food Corporation of

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:15.620
[Guest]: India.

00:58:15.620 --> 00:58:16.620
[Guest]: Okay.

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:20.380
[Guest]: Because what happens is now, so Food Corporation of India buys, and this is something we've

00:58:20.380 --> 00:58:26.700
[Guest]: discussed before, buys rice and wheat primarily directly from the farmers.

00:58:26.700 --> 00:58:30.180
[Guest]: Of late it's also bought pulses and oilseeds.

00:58:30.180 --> 00:58:35.460
[Guest]: Now it buys rice and wheat at a certain rate, but it sells them at a very, very low rate

00:58:35.460 --> 00:58:41.580
[Guest]: through the public distribution system, through the ration shops in order to fulfill the terms

00:58:41.580 --> 00:58:44.260
[Guest]: and conditions under the Food Securities Act.

00:58:44.260 --> 00:58:50.900
[Guest]: So obviously the difference is huge and this difference has to be refunded to the Food

00:58:50.900 --> 00:58:56.540
[Guest]: Corporation of India because otherwise, you know, the institution will collapse.

00:58:56.540 --> 00:59:01.540
[Guest]: And so what happens is that in every budget, the government has allocations towards food

00:59:01.540 --> 00:59:06.660
[Guest]: subsidy and a lot of this food subsidy allocation goes to compensate the Food Corporation of

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:08.060
[Guest]: India.

00:59:08.060 --> 00:59:14.380
[Guest]: But in the recent years, what has happened is that the Food Corporation of India is not

00:59:14.380 --> 00:59:16.660
[Guest]: being refunded totally.

00:59:16.660 --> 00:59:24.020
[Guest]: So as of March 2019, the money that the government owed the Food Corporation of India was more

00:59:24.020 --> 00:59:26.340
[Guest]: than 1,60,000 crore.

00:59:26.340 --> 00:59:31.820
[Guest]: Now if this is the case, you know, so if the government is not repaying the Food Corporation

00:59:31.820 --> 00:59:36.580
[Guest]: of India, the Food Corporation of India has to borrow that money from somewhere in order

00:59:36.580 --> 00:59:38.700
[Guest]: to continue to be in business.

00:59:38.700 --> 00:59:44.580
[Guest]: So of the 1,60,000 crore, close to more than 90,000 crore, I think 94,000 crore, if I remember

00:59:44.580 --> 00:59:49.380
[Guest]: the number correctly, has been borrowed from the National Small Savings Fund.

00:59:49.380 --> 00:59:54.220
[Guest]: Now why has it been borrowed from the National Small Savings Fund is because if they were

00:59:54.220 --> 00:59:59.460
[Guest]: to sort of borrow that money, you know, from the normal banking channels, then they would

00:59:59.460 --> 01:00:05.580
[Guest]: crowd out the private borrowers and then interest rates would go up even further.

01:00:05.580 --> 01:00:08.780
[Guest]: So it's a huge, huge mess.

01:00:08.780 --> 01:00:14.220
[Guest]: I mean, if you start digging into the accounts of the government, it's just bizarre beyond

01:00:14.220 --> 01:00:15.740
[Guest]: a point.

01:00:15.740 --> 01:00:20.820
[Guest]: So this is a I mean, so this is one example, this is one example of how a Ponzi schemes

01:00:20.820 --> 01:00:24.260
[Guest]: being run within the government.

01:00:24.260 --> 01:00:31.220
[Guest]: The other thing is, as we talked about the entire idea of a fiscal deficit of a perpetual

01:00:31.220 --> 01:00:39.340
[Guest]: fiscal deficit is nothing but a Ponzi scheme, I mean, if you if you look at it, now, I mean,

01:00:39.340 --> 01:00:45.940
[Guest]: any government, most governments across, you know, across the world, and this includes

01:00:45.940 --> 01:00:51.300
[Guest]: central and state governments, run a fiscal deficit, which basically means they don't

01:00:51.300 --> 01:00:53.340
[Guest]: earn as much as they spend.

01:00:53.340 --> 01:01:01.740
[Guest]: Now, in order to finance that fiscal deficit, they need to borrow money, okay, and they

01:01:01.740 --> 01:01:03.300
[Guest]: borrow money.

01:01:03.300 --> 01:01:08.060
[Guest]: And this fiscal deficit continues.

01:01:08.060 --> 01:01:15.860
[Guest]: So basically, what is happening here is that at any given point of time, if the money that

01:01:15.860 --> 01:01:21.820
[Guest]: has been borrowed by the government has to be repaid, how is it being repaid?

01:01:21.820 --> 01:01:25.580
[Guest]: It is being repaid by borrowing more money, okay.

01:01:25.580 --> 01:01:31.140
[Guest]: Now, how does the government borrow money, it borrows money by selling government securities,

01:01:31.140 --> 01:01:32.140
[Guest]: right.

01:01:32.140 --> 01:01:37.300
[Guest]: So these securities are sold, and the money comes in and it is used to pay off the government

01:01:37.300 --> 01:01:39.020
[Guest]: securities which are maturing.

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:44.940
[Guest]: Okay, now these new securities when their time to you know, comes when they are to mature,

01:01:44.940 --> 01:01:50.940
[Guest]: then the government borrows more money and repays this.

01:01:50.940 --> 01:01:56.380
[Guest]: And so the so the structure goes now, the thing here is this can only happen if the

01:01:56.380 --> 01:02:01.700
[Guest]: government is borrowing money in its own currency.

01:02:01.700 --> 01:02:02.700
[Guest]: Okay.

01:02:02.700 --> 01:02:09.420
[Guest]: Now, if you look at a lot of South American countries, they end up borrowing in dollars.

01:02:09.420 --> 01:02:13.740
[Guest]: Because you know, borrowing in dollar is cheaper than borrowing in your local currency.

01:02:13.740 --> 01:02:18.060
[Guest]: But the problem there is then, in order to repay those dollars, you need to earn those

01:02:18.060 --> 01:02:19.660
[Guest]: dollars as well.

01:02:19.660 --> 01:02:24.020
[Guest]: And in many cases, they don't have they are unable to earn those dollars.

01:02:24.020 --> 01:02:29.700
[Guest]: And then finally, they just default.

01:02:29.700 --> 01:02:33.540
[Guest]: So which is not going to happen in the Indian case, because the Indian government at least

01:02:33.540 --> 01:02:38.940
[Guest]: up until now borrows majorly in rupees.

01:02:38.940 --> 01:02:44.500
[Amit Varma]: And also apart from further borrowings, I suppose how they services debts is also of

01:02:44.500 --> 01:02:45.820
[Amit Varma]: future taxpayers.

01:02:45.820 --> 01:02:49.600
[Amit Varma]: So one way of doing that is the two ways of doing that one is that either you raise tax

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:55.340
[Amit Varma]: taxes in the future, which means future taxpayers are paying for your profligacy today, or you

01:02:55.340 --> 01:03:00.060
[Amit Varma]: can simply print money which leads to inflation, which is of course a tax on the poor.

01:03:00.060 --> 01:03:04.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's a future poor, who are therefore paying for your profligacy today.

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:10.220
[Amit Varma]: In either way, this is sort of a Ponzi scheme through time where effectively and this is

01:03:10.220 --> 01:03:15.020
[Amit Varma]: one of the classic criticisms of the Social Security in America, where you are basically

01:03:15.020 --> 01:03:20.620
[Amit Varma]: borrowing from future generations to spend on current ones, and which is expected to

01:03:20.620 --> 01:03:27.140
[Amit Varma]: be a crisis when for example, the baby boomers reach retirement age, and you know, at some

01:03:27.140 --> 01:03:32.860
[Amit Varma]: point in time, that scheme is expected to inevitably fall apart unless reformed drastically

01:03:32.860 --> 01:03:33.860
[Guest]: before.

01:03:33.860 --> 01:03:35.860
[Guest]: In fact, so I wanted to make a couple of more points.

01:03:35.860 --> 01:03:39.100
[Guest]: Now, you know, look at all the small savings schemes.

01:03:39.100 --> 01:03:44.060
[Guest]: If you speak to any corporate economist, he will tell you that the interest rates on small

01:03:44.060 --> 01:03:49.500
[Guest]: savings schemes need to come down, because they are higher than bank deposits.

01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:53.420
[Guest]: And in order to compete with small savings schemes, banks need to offer a higher rate

01:03:53.420 --> 01:03:54.480
[Guest]: of interest.

01:03:54.480 --> 01:03:58.220
[Guest]: And because banks are offering a higher rate of interest on the deposits, they need to

01:03:58.220 --> 01:04:00.740
[Guest]: charge a higher rate of interest on their loans.

01:04:00.740 --> 01:04:06.500
[Guest]: Now, the reason that, you know, interest on small savings schemes cannot come down dramatically

01:04:06.500 --> 01:04:10.500
[Guest]: is because the government wants money to keep coming into these schemes, because if money

01:04:10.500 --> 01:04:16.100
[Guest]: doesn't come into these schemes, how are they going to pay for all the you know, money which

01:04:16.100 --> 01:04:20.060
[Guest]: is maturing all the investment which is maturing.

01:04:20.060 --> 01:04:26.500
[Guest]: So which is why the rate of interest on on on on small savings schemes will always be

01:04:26.500 --> 01:04:31.020
[Guest]: higher than rate of interest on fixed deposits, because otherwise the entire Ponzi structure

01:04:31.020 --> 01:04:32.020
[Guest]: will collapse.

01:04:32.020 --> 01:04:37.660
[Guest]: Now, if the Ponzi structure collapses for a private guy, he can just run, but for a

01:04:37.660 --> 01:04:42.540
[Guest]: government, the government cannot run, right, the government will have to still pay all

01:04:42.540 --> 01:04:46.140
[Guest]: the money which is maturing, which will come from taxpayers, which will then have to come

01:04:46.140 --> 01:04:50.540
[Guest]: from, you know, other parts of the budget, which basically, and when it comes from the

01:04:50.540 --> 01:04:54.620
[Guest]: other parts of the budget, then the problem is that you have to cut expenditure somewhere

01:04:54.620 --> 01:04:56.900
[Guest]: else or raise taxes.

01:04:56.900 --> 01:04:59.220
[Guest]: So which is, you know, one part.

01:04:59.220 --> 01:05:05.540
[Guest]: The other interesting thing is, you know, is what economists call financial repression.

01:05:05.540 --> 01:05:13.940
[Guest]: Now, financial repression in the Indian context is forcing banks to buy government securities.

01:05:13.940 --> 01:05:20.660
[Guest]: So by law, banks have to invest a certain percentage of their deposits in government

01:05:20.660 --> 01:05:21.660
[Guest]: securities.

01:05:21.660 --> 01:05:25.460
[Guest]: I think as of now, it's around 18.75%.

01:05:25.460 --> 01:05:30.660
[Guest]: But banks on their own, I think, would probably have invested more than 25% of their money

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:32.100
[Guest]: in government securities.

01:05:32.100 --> 01:05:40.060
[Guest]: Now what this does is that it allows the government access to money, I mean, this is money which

01:05:40.060 --> 01:05:44.540
[Guest]: has to come into government securities, I mean, the same is the case with insurance

01:05:44.540 --> 01:05:49.360
[Guest]: companies where a certain proportion of, you know, money raised has to be compulsorily

01:05:49.360 --> 01:05:51.860
[Guest]: invested in government securities.

01:05:51.860 --> 01:05:57.760
[Guest]: So what this does is it keeps the interest rates lower than they actually would have

01:05:57.760 --> 01:06:04.980
[Guest]: been if the government did not force these institutions to buy government securities.

01:06:04.980 --> 01:06:08.060
[Amit Varma]: So there is, and,

01:06:08.060 --> 01:06:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And not just that, I'm assuming that the cost of borrowings for us common people from these

01:06:13.320 --> 01:06:18.420
[Amit Varma]: private banks is higher than it would otherwise would be because they have to make up somewhere

01:06:18.420 --> 01:06:21.260
[Amit Varma]: for the inefficient investments in government securities.

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:25.940
[Guest]: And you know, also, it is the interesting thing here is that this is also why the government

01:06:25.940 --> 01:06:30.700
[Guest]: doesn't let go of the Life Insurance Corporation of India, because ultimately, a lot of money

01:06:30.700 --> 01:06:37.780
[Guest]: that LIC raises through its so called insurance policies finds its way into, you know, government

01:06:37.780 --> 01:06:38.780
[Guest]: securities.

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:43.960
[Guest]: Also, you know, when the government is selling shares in companies that it owns, and which

01:06:43.960 --> 01:06:49.260
[Guest]: investors do not want to buy, then LIC has to come to the rescue of the government.

01:06:49.260 --> 01:06:54.540
[Guest]: And then this money helps in you know, financing the fiscal deficit and so the Ponzi scheme.

01:06:54.540 --> 01:07:00.780
[Amit Varma]: So now, as you pointed out in the first half of the show, Ponzi schemes run by private

01:07:00.780 --> 01:07:04.340
[Amit Varma]: parties have a natural end, at some point, they cannot continue anymore, and they fall

01:07:04.340 --> 01:07:05.340
[Amit Varma]: apart.

01:07:05.340 --> 01:07:06.340
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:07.340
[Amit Varma]: Does this fall apart?

01:07:07.340 --> 01:07:12.820
[Guest]: No, I mean, so this can continue as long as there are people, as long as there are people

01:07:12.820 --> 01:07:18.020
[Guest]: and as long as you know, as I said, I mean, as long as the money coming into the, you

01:07:18.020 --> 01:07:22.460
[Amit Varma]: know, government bonds is there, I mean, then which they can actually mandate as they do

01:07:22.460 --> 01:07:26.860
[Amit Varma]: in the case of private banks, you know, it can continue up until then, yes.

01:07:26.860 --> 01:07:30.620
[Amit Varma]: And we pay a price, which is sort of largely unseen.

01:07:30.620 --> 01:07:31.620
[Guest]: This is unseen.

01:07:31.620 --> 01:07:32.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is totally unseen.

01:07:32.620 --> 01:07:33.780
[Amit Varma]: This is totally unseen.

01:07:33.780 --> 01:07:37.980
[Amit Varma]: You'd also mentioned while we were chatting over our excellent respective ham and cheese

01:07:37.980 --> 01:07:44.780
[Amit Varma]: omelettes with some superb black coffee that there's a certain kind of naturally occurring

01:07:44.780 --> 01:07:47.540
[Amit Varma]: Ponzi scheme because of the nature of the financial system.

01:07:47.540 --> 01:07:49.380
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:07:49.380 --> 01:07:56.460
[Guest]: So, you know, there is a Nobel Prize winning economist called Robert Shiller, whose latest

01:07:56.460 --> 01:08:01.020
[Guest]: book Narrative Economics is brilliant, by the way, I'm also halfway through it.

01:08:01.020 --> 01:08:02.380
[Guest]: It's a great book.

01:08:02.380 --> 01:08:10.460
[Guest]: And also, you know, one thing about Shiller is that, I mean, unlike a lot of other economists,

01:08:10.460 --> 01:08:13.220
[Guest]: he is not out and out theoretical.

01:08:13.220 --> 01:08:15.220
[Guest]: And he does make predictions which come right.

01:08:15.220 --> 01:08:22.020
[Guest]: I mean, like, his book Irrational Exuberance came the first edition came almost a few months

01:08:22.020 --> 01:08:26.820
[Amit Varma]: before the dot com bubble burst early 99, I think, if I remember correctly, then he

01:08:26.820 --> 01:08:33.060
[Guest]: also his second edition of Irrational Exuberance came a couple of years before the real estate

01:08:33.060 --> 01:08:34.940
[Amit Varma]: bubble burst.

01:08:34.940 --> 01:08:38.740
[Amit Varma]: So he does have a I also make good predictions like this episode is going to be released

01:08:38.740 --> 01:08:39.740
[Amit Varma]: on this coming Monday.

01:08:39.740 --> 01:08:45.660
[Guest]: That's a very bad joke, even by your standards.

01:08:45.660 --> 01:08:54.300
[Guest]: So yeah, so Shiller essentially talks about, you know, naturally occurring Ponzi schemes.

01:08:54.300 --> 01:08:59.220
[Guest]: And so obviously, he calls them naturally occurring Ponzi schemes because they happen

01:08:59.220 --> 01:09:04.700
[Guest]: without the contravents of a fraudulent manager.

01:09:04.700 --> 01:09:12.300
[Guest]: And so what he essentially says is, and I'm paraphrasing here, when speculative prices

01:09:12.300 --> 01:09:17.540
[Guest]: in the stock market, I mean, share prices go up, creating successes for some investors.

01:09:17.540 --> 01:09:22.820
[Guest]: This may attract public attention, promote word of mouth enthusiasm and heighten expectations

01:09:22.820 --> 01:09:24.820
[Guest]: for further price increases.

01:09:24.820 --> 01:09:26.940
[Guest]: The stock market is the best example.

01:09:26.940 --> 01:09:30.580
[Guest]: Stories about stock markets going up spread very fast.

01:09:30.580 --> 01:09:34.780
[Guest]: Investors in an optimistic mood might want to buy stock and take the stock price further

01:09:34.780 --> 01:09:35.780
[Guest]: up.

01:09:35.780 --> 01:09:39.620
[Guest]: This leads to more investors entering the market, fueling an even greater price rise

01:09:39.620 --> 01:09:43.060
[Guest]: and the cycle gets repeated over and over again.

01:09:43.060 --> 01:09:49.420
[Guest]: As Shiller writes, when prices go up a number of times, investors are rewarded by price

01:09:49.420 --> 01:09:54.660
[Guest]: movements in these markets, just as they are in Ponzi schemes, OK?

01:09:54.660 --> 01:09:59.880
[Guest]: Now, the high prices are not sustainable since they are driven by unrealistic expectations

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:01.460
[Guest]: of further price increases.

01:10:01.460 --> 01:10:03.980
[Guest]: The bubble eventually bursts and price crashes.

01:10:03.980 --> 01:10:09.620
[Guest]: Now, I mean, this works in, you know, so many different cases.

01:10:09.620 --> 01:10:14.660
[Guest]: I mean, you look at the entire, you know, the Modi bull run, the so-called Modi bull

01:10:14.660 --> 01:10:18.140
[Guest]: run, which has been on since September 2013.

01:10:18.140 --> 01:10:26.120
[Guest]: I mean, you know, stock brokerages have essentially been driving this story over and over again

01:10:26.120 --> 01:10:27.820
[Guest]: in various forms.

01:10:27.820 --> 01:10:34.700
[Guest]: But ultimately, the earnings of the companies haven't caught on to the price increases.

01:10:34.700 --> 01:10:40.020
[Guest]: So it's just the money that keeps coming in, which, you know, which drives up the prices,

01:10:40.020 --> 01:10:45.220
[Guest]: making it a beautiful example of a naturally occurring Ponzi scheme.

01:10:45.220 --> 01:10:53.900
[Guest]: Or if you look at real estate, I mean, the rally between almost 2002, 2003 to 2011, 12,

01:10:53.900 --> 01:10:59.500
[Guest]: 13, I mean, people used to just, you know, blindly invest in real estate because a whole

01:10:59.500 --> 01:11:03.520
[Guest]: generation had seen just prices going up.

01:11:03.520 --> 01:11:09.340
[Guest]: But beyond a point, you know, the prices reached a stage where it wasn't just, I mean, prices

01:11:09.340 --> 01:11:13.620
[Guest]: were going up not because there was genuine demand for these homes.

01:11:13.620 --> 01:11:17.700
[Guest]: They were going up because there were these investors who had money and they were buying

01:11:17.700 --> 01:11:18.700
[Guest]: and flipping.

01:11:18.700 --> 01:11:22.260
[Guest]: And ultimately, you know, even that game stopped.

01:11:22.260 --> 01:11:26.940
[Guest]: And if you look at how, you know, real estate has gone in the last five, six years, it's

01:11:26.940 --> 01:11:32.060
[Guest]: it's by, you know, it's by and large been a mess, primarily because the prices reached

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:37.660
[Guest]: a stage where they just became unsustainable and, and prices continue to remain high, which

01:11:37.660 --> 01:11:39.820
[Amit Varma]: is why the recovery hasn't happened.

01:11:39.820 --> 01:11:45.580
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you and I have an excellent episode on why, despite demand having gone down in

01:11:45.580 --> 01:11:49.800
[Amit Varma]: real estate prices haven't followed suit, which is not what you would expect, theoretically.

01:11:49.800 --> 01:11:54.380
[Amit Varma]: But I guess all bubbles in a sense, work in the Ponzi structure in the sense that let's

01:11:54.380 --> 01:11:59.500
[Amit Varma]: say that there is a share of a company which should logically given sales and given revenues

01:11:59.500 --> 01:12:02.660
[Amit Varma]: and all of that sell, you know, within a narrow band.

01:12:02.660 --> 01:12:06.540
[Amit Varma]: But when it goes above that, it's basically investors are then buying it expecting it

01:12:06.540 --> 01:12:10.620
[Amit Varma]: to rise further, which brings a greater fool theory into play, because they are buying

01:12:10.620 --> 01:12:13.860
[Amit Varma]: at a high price, but they don't care that it's too high, because you know, someone will

01:12:13.860 --> 01:12:18.860
[Amit Varma]: buy it for higher, which is again a classic case of a later investor paying off an earlier

01:12:18.860 --> 01:12:19.860
[Amit Varma]: investment.

01:12:19.860 --> 01:12:23.740
[Amit Varma]: And this continues to a point where because of all kinds of reasons, maybe the internal

01:12:23.740 --> 01:12:30.300
[Amit Varma]: logic breaks down, or external events cause a crash, where it all kinds of falls apart.

01:12:30.300 --> 01:12:33.220
[Amit Varma]: And the last guy left holding the can goes down.

01:12:33.220 --> 01:12:37.460
[Amit Varma]: But as you know, Chuck Prince, who was then head of Citibank famously said in 2007, when

01:12:37.460 --> 01:12:41.060
[Amit Varma]: he was asked about this about, you know, why do you keep participating in a bubble and

01:12:41.060 --> 01:12:47.300
[Amit Varma]: Prince said, quote, as long as the music's playing, you have to dance, stop, quote, and,

01:12:47.300 --> 01:12:48.860
[Amit Varma]: and that's often what happens.

01:12:48.860 --> 01:12:53.940
[Amit Varma]: So, all these people participating in this Ponzi scheme of stock market bubbles or real

01:12:53.940 --> 01:12:58.740
[Amit Varma]: estate bubbles aren't necessarily fools, they're behaving rationally, because they see the

01:12:58.740 --> 01:13:05.700
[Amit Varma]: high probability of a greater fool along the road, so that they can make a profit.

01:13:05.700 --> 01:13:10.900
[Guest]: And thus history continues to talk about naturally occurring Ponzi schemes.

01:13:10.900 --> 01:13:16.260
[Guest]: They've been described beautifully in this book, written by Charles Mackey, which was

01:13:16.260 --> 01:13:21.380
[Guest]: published in 1841, Madness of Crowds, Memoirs of Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the

01:13:21.380 --> 01:13:22.380
[Guest]: Madness of Crowds.

01:13:22.380 --> 01:13:28.860
[Guest]: It's, I mean, highly recommended not, you know, if you read it, not every chapter will

01:13:28.860 --> 01:13:29.860
[Guest]: be interesting.

01:13:29.860 --> 01:13:31.900
[Guest]: But some of the chapters are very, very interesting.

01:13:31.900 --> 01:13:36.620
[Guest]: And it's freely available on the link all these books we mentioned from the show notes.

01:13:36.620 --> 01:13:42.460
[Guest]: So in this book, you know, he describes the tulip mania in Holland, in the 1630s.

01:13:42.460 --> 01:13:49.260
[Guest]: The first account of tulips in Europe is from 1559, when a collector of exotic flora, Counsellor

01:13:49.260 --> 01:13:54.340
[Guest]: Hermat, received a consignment of tulip bulbs from a friend in Constantinople, which is

01:13:54.340 --> 01:13:58.540
[Guest]: now Istanbul, which he planted in his garden in Germany.

01:13:58.540 --> 01:14:01.180
[Guest]: His tulips drew a good deal of attention.

01:14:01.180 --> 01:14:06.020
[Guest]: In the following years, this flower became more and more popular among the upper classes,

01:14:06.020 --> 01:14:10.940
[Guest]: particularly in Germany and Holland, where it became a custom to order bulbs at an exorbitant

01:14:10.940 --> 01:14:13.540
[Guest]: price directly from Constantinople.

01:14:13.540 --> 01:14:18.780
[Guest]: Up to 1634, this custom became increasingly common, and from that, affluent society in

01:14:18.780 --> 01:14:22.260
[Guest]: Holland considered a lack of tulip collection to be of poor taste.

01:14:22.260 --> 01:14:24.740
[Guest]: So you need to have tulips in your house.

01:14:24.740 --> 01:14:29.020
[Guest]: Year after year, tulip prices rose, finally reaching astronomical heights.

01:14:29.020 --> 01:14:36.140
[Guest]: By 1636, the demand for tulip bulbs had risen drastically, and people started to trade them

01:14:36.140 --> 01:14:40.660
[Guest]: in exchanges across many towns in Holland.

01:14:40.660 --> 01:14:45.540
[Guest]: Tulips were bought by well-to-do collectors as well as by agents and speculators.

01:14:45.540 --> 01:14:49.700
[Guest]: At the smallest price drop, they would buy only to sell it later at a profit.

01:14:49.700 --> 01:14:51.900
[Guest]: Many individuals suddenly grew rich.

01:14:51.900 --> 01:14:55.980
[Guest]: A golden bait hung tempting out before the people.

01:14:55.980 --> 01:15:02.100
[Guest]: One after the other, they rushed into tulip markets like flies around a honeypot.

01:15:02.100 --> 01:15:06.340
[Guest]: At last, however, the more prudent ones began to see the folly that this could not last

01:15:06.340 --> 01:15:07.340
[Guest]: forever.

01:15:07.340 --> 01:15:10.940
[Guest]: Rich people no longer bought the flowers to keep them in their gardens, but to sell them

01:15:10.940 --> 01:15:12.900
[Guest]: again at a profit.

01:15:12.900 --> 01:15:16.660
[Guest]: It was seen that somebody must lose fearfully in the end.

01:15:16.660 --> 01:15:20.900
[Guest]: As this conviction spread, prices fell and never rose again.

01:15:20.900 --> 01:15:25.780
[Guest]: Now, you know, so this is how the Dutch tulip bubble played out.

01:15:25.780 --> 01:15:30.300
[Guest]: In fact, the tulip bubble is still playing out very well for Holland.

01:15:30.300 --> 01:15:35.180
[Guest]: I mean, you know, people from all over the world go there to see the tulips.

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:40.180
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, the question that I would ask for you to ponder about is how is buying tulips

01:15:40.180 --> 01:15:45.540
[Amit Varma]: for investment back in the day different from, say, buying art for investment today?

01:15:45.540 --> 01:15:47.700
[Guest]: Because at the end of the day, it's all about people's perceptions.

01:15:47.700 --> 01:15:48.700
[Guest]: 100 percent.

01:15:48.700 --> 01:15:52.540
[Guest]: I mean, see, value is perception at the end of the day.

01:15:52.540 --> 01:15:55.460
[Guest]: You take your shots and it goes where it goes.

01:15:55.460 --> 01:15:56.460
[Guest]: Yes.

01:15:56.460 --> 01:16:01.020
[Guest]: So, you know, we were talking about, you know, naturally occurring Ponzi schemes.

01:16:01.020 --> 01:16:07.180
[Guest]: Now, if you look at the way a lot of private CEOs of private companies, private banks talk

01:16:07.180 --> 01:16:16.780
[Guest]: these days, I mean, you know, they are perpetually trying to project a positive economic environment.

01:16:16.780 --> 01:16:22.060
[Guest]: I mean, if you ask them how well the economy is doing, I mean, they're rarely negative.

01:16:22.060 --> 01:16:28.180
[Guest]: I mean, and I mean, one reason, obviously, is that no, no CEO in India wants to irritate

01:16:28.180 --> 01:16:29.180
[Guest]: the government.

01:16:29.180 --> 01:16:34.860
[Guest]: That is a perpetual given, but beyond that, you know, they have a personal incentive in

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:41.220
[Guest]: ensuring that their stock prices keep going up simply because they own a lot of stock

01:16:41.220 --> 01:16:42.220
[Guest]: options.

01:16:42.220 --> 01:16:48.820
[Guest]: So, it is in their interest to ensure that they keep talking up the stock as well as

01:16:48.820 --> 01:16:49.820
[Guest]: the economy.

01:16:49.820 --> 01:16:56.260
[Guest]: So, this is another excellent example of a spin off of a naturally occurring Ponzi scheme.

01:16:56.260 --> 01:17:01.300
[Amit Varma]: And added incentive is not just a personal stock options, but also that they are judged

01:17:01.300 --> 01:17:03.380
[Amit Varma]: on short term results.

01:17:03.380 --> 01:17:07.540
[Amit Varma]: And one metric for those short term results is how well is the company's stock doing.

01:17:07.540 --> 01:17:15.020
[Amit Varma]: So, it is more profitable for them to say, do and say things which impact the short term

01:17:15.020 --> 01:17:19.820
[Amit Varma]: performance of the company in the stock market, rather than the long term fiscal health of

01:17:19.820 --> 01:17:20.820
[Guest]: the company, for example.

01:17:20.820 --> 01:17:22.540
[Amit Varma]: Not very different from our politicians.

01:17:22.540 --> 01:17:26.060
[Amit Varma]: Not very different from our politicians who are always fighting for elections and therefore

01:17:26.060 --> 01:17:28.020
[Guest]: are in perpetual campaign mode.

01:17:28.020 --> 01:17:33.100
[Guest]: So, which again tells you that their structure is also very Ponzi in nature.

01:17:33.100 --> 01:17:37.740
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, one interesting thing regarding CEOs is the Lake Wobegon effect.

01:17:37.740 --> 01:17:38.740
[Amit Varma]: Have you heard of that?

01:17:38.740 --> 01:17:39.740
[Amit Varma]: No.

01:17:39.740 --> 01:17:43.260
[Amit Varma]: So, a guy called Garrison Keillor wrote a book, wrote a novel called Lake Wobegon Days,

01:17:43.260 --> 01:17:47.420
[Amit Varma]: which was about a town called Lake Wobegon, where everybody was above average.

01:17:47.420 --> 01:17:52.380
[Amit Varma]: Now, you might, of course, ask with your mathematical mind, how can everybody be above average because

01:17:52.380 --> 01:17:55.540
[Amit Varma]: the average is on average, they'll be average.

01:17:55.540 --> 01:18:00.260
[Amit Varma]: And that has led to this thing called the Lake Wobegon effect on the compensation of

01:18:00.260 --> 01:18:06.260
[Amit Varma]: CEOs, where what happens is that every time a company wants to hire a CEO, whoever they

01:18:06.260 --> 01:18:12.980
[Amit Varma]: want to hire, will demand a higher compensation than the market under the logic and the previous

01:18:12.980 --> 01:18:16.660
[Amit Varma]: guy under the logic that look, you're hiring somebody better, that's why you're hiring

01:18:16.660 --> 01:18:21.820
[Amit Varma]: somebody otherwise, why you know, and what happens because of this is that CEO salaries

01:18:21.820 --> 01:18:28.300
[Amit Varma]: tend to rise and rise with reference to previous CEO salaries, and to the average of the market,

01:18:28.300 --> 01:18:33.340
[Amit Varma]: because they have to get more than average, until a point where they rise beyond any,

01:18:33.340 --> 01:18:36.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, rational reasoning, all based on supply and demand, of course, because the

01:18:36.980 --> 01:18:39.580
[Amit Varma]: companies also have no choice.

01:18:39.580 --> 01:18:42.100
[Guest]: And that just so that's known as sort of the Lake Wobegon effect.

01:18:42.100 --> 01:18:47.660
[Guest]: So just to add to it, no, I mean, I just remembered that, I think up until the early 90s, the

01:18:47.660 --> 01:18:55.140
[Guest]: Securities and Exchange Commission in the US did not ask companies to compulsorily disclose

01:18:55.140 --> 01:19:02.540
[Guest]: CEO salaries, then they thought that, you know, it would be better, more transparency

01:19:02.540 --> 01:19:03.540
[Guest]: and all that.

01:19:03.540 --> 01:19:08.260
[Guest]: So, so they said, Okay, now, you know, all companies have to compulsorily declare CEO

01:19:08.260 --> 01:19:09.260
[Amit Varma]: salaries.

01:19:09.260 --> 01:19:14.740
[Guest]: Yeah, what did what this did was that up until then, the CEOs did not know the salaries of

01:19:14.740 --> 01:19:18.820
[Guest]: other CEOs, now, they knew the salaries of other CEOs.

01:19:18.820 --> 01:19:24.020
[Guest]: So when they were negotiating, obviously, they wanted higher salaries, and the net net

01:19:24.020 --> 01:19:29.220
[Guest]: effect was that, you know, CEO salaries instead of, you know, so the idea was that once you

01:19:29.220 --> 01:19:33.540
[Guest]: sort of declare CEO salaries and put them in public domain, then you know, the shareholders

01:19:33.540 --> 01:19:34.540
[Guest]: would take over.

01:19:34.540 --> 01:19:38.460
[Guest]: And if they felt that the CEO is sort of getting more than he should, I mean, then there would

01:19:38.460 --> 01:19:39.460
[Guest]: be some activism.

01:19:39.460 --> 01:19:41.020
[Guest]: And so all that never happened.

01:19:41.020 --> 01:19:46.180
[Guest]: But what happened was that the the benchmark of CEO salaries was set very, very clearly

01:19:46.180 --> 01:19:50.820
[Guest]: and salaries instead of, you know, moderating, they actually inevitably, another example

01:19:50.820 --> 01:19:54.860
[Amit Varma]: of a similar in a very different context, but a similar effect and similar unintended

01:19:54.860 --> 01:19:57.780
[Amit Varma]: consequences is the anti defection law in India.

01:19:57.780 --> 01:20:01.180
[Amit Varma]: The anti defection law in India, I had an episode on this with Varun Mitra very old

01:20:01.180 --> 01:20:06.240
[Amit Varma]: episode came about in about I think 1986, or around that time mid 80s.

01:20:06.240 --> 01:20:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And the idea was very good.

01:20:07.240 --> 01:20:11.820
[Amit Varma]: The idea was that look, you know, MPs keep defecting to other parties for money, let's

01:20:11.820 --> 01:20:14.140
[Amit Varma]: have a law by which they cannot defect.

01:20:14.140 --> 01:20:17.820
[Amit Varma]: And they have to vote with their party in parliament, there is no option, they just

01:20:17.820 --> 01:20:18.920
[Amit Varma]: have to.

01:20:18.920 --> 01:20:23.980
[Amit Varma]: And the result of that the unintended consequences of that is that all parliamentary debate in

01:20:23.980 --> 01:20:28.900
[Amit Varma]: India has completely stopped earlier, especially around the time of independence, you had a

01:20:28.900 --> 01:20:34.020
[Amit Varma]: tradition of lively erudite debates in parliaments on all kinds of issues.

01:20:34.020 --> 01:20:39.220
[Amit Varma]: Today, you have no debates at all, except for, you know, performatives, performatively

01:20:39.220 --> 01:20:43.780
[Amit Varma]: speaking to your own side, but you have effectively have no parliamentary debate anymore, because

01:20:43.780 --> 01:20:46.180
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't matter, you have to vote with your party.

01:20:46.180 --> 01:20:49.740
[Amit Varma]: And you could effectively run parliament from an Excel sheet.

01:20:49.740 --> 01:20:53.820
[Amit Varma]: I don't even understand why the members have to be physically present, because the anti

01:20:53.820 --> 01:21:00.820
[Amit Varma]: defection law renders them completely impotent in terms of actual decision making or affecting

01:21:00.820 --> 01:21:08.100
[Amit Varma]: the course of parliament, but that is a digression, let us get back to smaller frauds, Ponzi frauds.

01:21:08.100 --> 01:21:10.140
[Guest]: Oh, even bigger ones, actually.

01:21:10.140 --> 01:21:13.340
[Amit Varma]: So, speaking of something bigger, you had mentioned to me while we were having breakfast

01:21:13.340 --> 01:21:20.380
[Amit Varma]: Vivek that Ponzi schemes are not just you know, private frauds run by companies or even

01:21:20.380 --> 01:21:25.660
[Amit Varma]: governmental ones within a country, but they can take on a geopolitical scale and impact

01:21:25.660 --> 01:21:28.020
[Amit Varma]: the entire financial system of the world.

01:21:28.020 --> 01:21:29.540
[Guest]: Can you elaborate on that a bit?

01:21:29.540 --> 01:21:33.900
[Guest]: So this is, you know, more we're talking more in terms of structure, rather than, you know,

01:21:33.900 --> 01:21:35.980
[Guest]: there's no fraud element here.

01:21:35.980 --> 01:21:45.220
[Guest]: So I mean, if you look at the US dollar, now, the way the global financial system evolved

01:21:45.220 --> 01:21:50.300
[Guest]: post 1945, the dollar came to be at the heart of it.

01:21:50.300 --> 01:21:54.540
[Guest]: And you know, this obviously started at the Bretton Woods conference in New Hampshire

01:21:54.540 --> 01:22:00.100
[Guest]: in July 1944, where it was decided that, you know, the dollar would be one currency which

01:22:00.100 --> 01:22:04.060
[Guest]: would continue to be convertible into gold.

01:22:04.060 --> 01:22:09.980
[Guest]: Now, because of this, what happened was that countries started having their reserves, their

01:22:09.980 --> 01:22:14.460
[Guest]: international reserves in dollars, because dollar was the only currency convertible into

01:22:14.460 --> 01:22:15.460
[Guest]: gold.

01:22:15.460 --> 01:22:19.980
[Guest]: Before that, they used to have, you know, their reserves in the British pound because

01:22:19.980 --> 01:22:25.740
[Guest]: pound was also convertible into gold, but post the Second World War, because America

01:22:25.740 --> 01:22:30.980
[Guest]: had most of the monetary gold in the world, it sort of became came at the heart of the

01:22:30.980 --> 01:22:32.340
[Guest]: global financial system.

01:22:32.340 --> 01:22:37.540
[Guest]: Now, what has happened is because the you know, of this over the years, the much of

01:22:37.540 --> 01:22:43.540
[Guest]: the international trade has also moved to dollars, before that it was sort of split

01:22:43.540 --> 01:22:47.900
[Guest]: between you know, pound and dollar and so on, and so on and so forth.

01:22:47.900 --> 01:22:55.180
[Guest]: Now, now let's take the case of when I'm talking very simple terms here, let's take the case

01:22:55.180 --> 01:22:57.420
[Guest]: of United States and China.

01:22:57.420 --> 01:23:03.820
[Guest]: Now, the US is a net importer from China, it buys a lot of goods produced in China.

01:23:03.820 --> 01:23:07.300
[Guest]: Now, China obviously gets paid in dollars.

01:23:07.300 --> 01:23:13.940
[Guest]: Now, when a Chinese exporter gets these dollars back into China, he has to convert them into

01:23:13.940 --> 01:23:16.060
[Guest]: Yuan.

01:23:16.060 --> 01:23:20.260
[Guest]: And when he converts them into, he has to convert them into Yuan, because his expenses,

01:23:20.260 --> 01:23:22.380
[Guest]: his reporting everything is in Yuan.

01:23:22.380 --> 01:23:28.140
[Guest]: So these dollars then land up at as foreign exchange reserves at the People's Bank of

01:23:28.140 --> 01:23:30.420
[Guest]: China, which is the Chinese Central Bank.

01:23:30.420 --> 01:23:35.900
[Guest]: Now, these dollars can, you know, either continue remaining in the remaining with the People's

01:23:35.900 --> 01:23:39.460
[Guest]: Bank of China, or they can be invested somewhere.

01:23:39.460 --> 01:23:44.820
[Guest]: So then they are invested, the dollars are invested in American government securities.

01:23:44.820 --> 01:23:52.180
[Guest]: Now, because China earns, you know, so many, you know, a lot of dollars, a lot of dollars,

01:23:52.180 --> 01:23:56.580
[Guest]: more than a trillion dollars have been invested in American government securities.

01:23:56.580 --> 01:24:02.220
[Guest]: The same is the case with Japan, Japan has also invested more than a trillion dollars.

01:24:02.220 --> 01:24:09.440
[Guest]: So because so much foreign money comes into US government securities, the interest rates

01:24:09.440 --> 01:24:15.820
[Guest]: that the US government needs to offer on those securities becomes very low, because you know,

01:24:15.820 --> 01:24:17.260
[Guest]: the demand is huge.

01:24:17.260 --> 01:24:24.940
[Guest]: Now, when the interest rate that the US government is paying on its bonds is low, that becomes

01:24:24.940 --> 01:24:31.820
[Guest]: a benchmark for the overall interest rate scenario in the US, which is also low.

01:24:31.820 --> 01:24:37.900
[Guest]: So at lower interest rates, you know, people can borrow and buy stuff.

01:24:37.900 --> 01:24:42.740
[Guest]: And a lot of this stuff that gets bought is made in China.

01:24:42.740 --> 01:24:49.460
[Guest]: And because of this, you know, dollars which come back into the US in and get invested

01:24:49.460 --> 01:24:56.540
[Guest]: in US government treasuries ensure that interest rates are low, and consumer demand is high.

01:24:56.540 --> 01:25:01.780
[Guest]: And because of this Chinese companies benefit and more dollars go into China.

01:25:01.780 --> 01:25:08.300
[Guest]: And then these dollars are converted into Yuan, and then find their way back into the

01:25:08.300 --> 01:25:13.780
[Guest]: US government treasury securities, and again, ensure that interest rates continue to remain

01:25:13.780 --> 01:25:14.780
[Guest]: low.

01:25:14.780 --> 01:25:19.300
[Guest]: So there is a there is a cycle, there is a structure to it, where money goes from the

01:25:19.300 --> 01:25:24.980
[Guest]: US to China and comes back to the US and in the process ensures lower interest rates.

01:25:24.980 --> 01:25:30.820
[Guest]: It also ensures that the world continues the world trading system, so to say continues

01:25:30.820 --> 01:25:33.380
[Guest]: to be on the US dollar, right?

01:25:33.380 --> 01:25:38.660
[Guest]: I mean, it gives us an exorbitant privilege where in every country in the world needs

01:25:38.660 --> 01:25:43.540
[Guest]: to earn these dollars, the US can simply print it.

01:25:43.540 --> 01:25:50.420
[Guest]: Now, Donald Trump has this thing in his head that in order to make America great again,

01:25:50.420 --> 01:25:56.180
[Guest]: he has, you know, American imports have to come down, and exports have to go up.

01:25:56.180 --> 01:26:01.180
[Amit Varma]: In fact, we've had a couple of episodes on the trade deficit and, you know, as a point

01:26:01.180 --> 01:26:04.660
[Amit Varma]: that we repeatedly keep making on different fora is that there's nothing wrong with the

01:26:04.660 --> 01:26:05.660
[Amit Varma]: trade deficit.

01:26:05.660 --> 01:26:08.820
[Amit Varma]: I mean, ultimately, all trade happens to mutual benefit.

01:26:08.820 --> 01:26:13.380
[Amit Varma]: You know, I have a trade deficit with my domestic health, for example, you know, I pay her every

01:26:13.380 --> 01:26:15.860
[Amit Varma]: month she never pays, she buys anything from me.

01:26:15.860 --> 01:26:19.580
[Amit Varma]: And that's fine, because we're both benefiting, it's at mutually agreed terms and trade happens

01:26:19.580 --> 01:26:22.540
[Amit Varma]: between the individuals of both countries.

01:26:22.540 --> 01:26:26.820
[Amit Varma]: But Trump, for some reason, sees the world in zero sum ways, and therefore he thinks

01:26:26.820 --> 01:26:32.580
[Amit Varma]: that this trade deficit is a problem that if they are making more dollars, and we must

01:26:32.580 --> 01:26:33.580
[Amit Varma]: be losing something.

01:26:33.580 --> 01:26:34.580
[Guest]: Right.

01:26:34.580 --> 01:26:38.460
[Guest]: So basically, you know, the entire the trade system as it has evolved with, you know, money

01:26:38.460 --> 01:26:43.700
[Guest]: finding its way, trade and financial system, with money, all these dollars from all these

01:26:43.700 --> 01:26:50.020
[Guest]: countries, you know, China is just with one example, but Japan, Saudi Arabia, even India,

01:26:50.020 --> 01:26:53.820
[Guest]: I mean, all these dollars find not all but a lot of these dollars find their way back

01:26:53.820 --> 01:26:54.820
[Guest]: into the US.

01:26:54.820 --> 01:26:59.180
[Guest]: And this essentially ensures that the interest rates in US continue to remain low.

01:26:59.180 --> 01:27:06.580
[Guest]: Now, there is a global trade war on currently with and Trump is making it more and more

01:27:06.580 --> 01:27:11.060
[Guest]: difficult for Americans to import goods from China.

01:27:11.060 --> 01:27:12.060
[Guest]: Okay.

01:27:12.060 --> 01:27:18.500
[Guest]: Now, if America doesn't import goods from China, then China doesn't earn those dollars,

01:27:18.500 --> 01:27:19.500
[Guest]: right.

01:27:19.500 --> 01:27:23.500
[Guest]: So one impact of that is that those dollars then again, don't find their way back into

01:27:23.500 --> 01:27:24.660
[Guest]: America.

01:27:24.660 --> 01:27:30.460
[Guest]: The other impact is that if China doesn't own on those dollars, it also doesn't earn

01:27:30.460 --> 01:27:33.980
[Guest]: money to buy stuff from other countries.

01:27:33.980 --> 01:27:38.580
[Guest]: So if it had earned that money, and it had bought stuff from other countries, those dollars

01:27:38.580 --> 01:27:42.900
[Guest]: would also eventually find its way back into America and ensure lower interest rates.

01:27:42.900 --> 01:27:47.780
[Guest]: So Trump is essentially attacking his own people, his own people in and he's attacking

01:27:47.780 --> 01:27:53.940
[Guest]: a system which has helped the US and which has helped the dollar continue to be at the

01:27:53.940 --> 01:27:57.100
[Guest]: heart of the global financial system.

01:27:57.100 --> 01:28:01.620
[Guest]: So so and in a way, you know, he's he's essentially trying to break the Ponzi structure.

01:28:01.620 --> 01:28:06.660
[Guest]: But you know, if and when and if it if he is successful at doing it, it will eventually

01:28:06.660 --> 01:28:13.060
[Guest]: end up hurting Americans because all these dollars will not come back to America, interest

01:28:13.060 --> 01:28:14.300
[Guest]: rates can go up.

01:28:14.300 --> 01:28:18.740
[Guest]: And if interest rates go up the entire, you know, the consumption culture on which essentially,

01:28:18.740 --> 01:28:24.020
[Guest]: you know, which is the great big American dream, will will sort of virtuous cycle becomes

01:28:24.020 --> 01:28:25.020
[Guest]: a vicious cycle.

01:28:25.020 --> 01:28:30.500
[Guest]: So this is another, you know, the, I mean, this in this case, the irony is that the the

01:28:30.500 --> 01:28:38.580
