[Amit Varma]: without an Aadhaar number, you don't get the notification.

01:30:24.860 --> 01:30:27.100
[Amit Varma]: That's coming up next.

01:30:27.100 --> 01:30:30.860
[Amit Varma]: Moving on from this, you know, so we've discussed different kinds of Ponzi schemes, whether

01:30:30.860 --> 01:30:36.340
[Amit Varma]: private or public, we've discussed these Ponzi structures, which are overlaid over certain

01:30:36.340 --> 01:30:43.020
[Amit Varma]: systems, whether within the financial world or in geopolitics or whatever, what sort of

01:30:43.020 --> 01:30:48.740
[Amit Varma]: also intrigues me is that, listen, we are the only species with Ponzi schemes, partly

01:30:48.740 --> 01:30:55.380
[Amit Varma]: because we are the only species which trades in narratives, we make stories about the world

01:30:55.380 --> 01:30:59.360
[Amit Varma]: and they explain the world to us and they are how we navigate the world, which makes

01:30:59.360 --> 01:31:08.020
[Amit Varma]: us extremely susceptible to believing in these Ponzi schemes and get-rich schemes.

01:31:08.020 --> 01:31:10.980
[Amit Varma]: What are sort of the different, and I know you've written about this in your paper, and

01:31:10.980 --> 01:31:14.620
[Amit Varma]: of course, both you and I for many, many years have been writing about cognitive biases and

01:31:14.620 --> 01:31:17.780
[Amit Varma]: logical fallacies and all of them apply here.

01:31:17.780 --> 01:31:20.380
[Amit Varma]: What are some of the main ones you would say have something to do with it?

01:31:20.380 --> 01:31:25.500
[Guest]: So I mean, obviously, as fundamental as this may sound, I guess the main factor that sort

01:31:25.500 --> 01:31:29.140
[Guest]: of encourages Ponzi schemes is the herd mentality.

01:31:29.140 --> 01:31:35.220
[Guest]: So there's a beautiful quote in Robert Schiller's book, Irrational Exuberance, and this is how

01:31:35.220 --> 01:31:36.220
[Guest]: it goes.

01:31:36.220 --> 01:31:41.180
[Guest]: A fundamental observation about human society is that people who communicate regularly with

01:31:41.180 --> 01:31:42.860
[Guest]: one another think similarly.

01:31:42.860 --> 01:31:49.300
[Guest]: There is at any place and in any time a zeitgeist, a spirit of times.

01:31:49.300 --> 01:31:55.780
[Guest]: So what happens is if a person wants to invest, the chances are that he will look around to

01:31:55.780 --> 01:32:00.020
[Guest]: see what his friends, family, etc., etc., are doing with their money.

01:32:00.020 --> 01:32:04.700
[Guest]: And when they see that the friends, etc., are investing in a particular scheme where

01:32:04.700 --> 01:32:10.300
[Guest]: they have made money, so they automatically sort of end up investing there because the

01:32:10.300 --> 01:32:16.660
[Guest]: assumption is that, okay, this guy I know and he's made his money, so it should generally

01:32:16.660 --> 01:32:17.660
[Guest]: be safe.

01:32:17.660 --> 01:32:20.420
[Guest]: People don't go inquiring about it.

01:32:20.420 --> 01:32:24.300
[Guest]: And this is true about not just Ponzi schemes, it's true about, I mean, look at why people

01:32:24.300 --> 01:32:30.060
[Guest]: buy LIC policies, I mean, they buy LIC policies because, you know, the guy selling them the

01:32:30.060 --> 01:32:34.260
[Guest]: policy is known to them, he's a relative, or they've seen people all around them buy

01:32:34.260 --> 01:32:35.260
[Guest]: LIC policies.

01:32:35.260 --> 01:32:39.980
[Amit Varma]: LIC agents are sort of a downmarket version of the Amway agent, in a sense.

01:32:39.980 --> 01:32:43.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it's the same thing, I mean, it's largely the same thing.

01:32:43.500 --> 01:32:45.860
[Amit Varma]: You don't recommend buying LIC schemes, right?

01:32:45.860 --> 01:32:46.860
[Guest]: Not at all.

01:32:46.860 --> 01:32:50.580
[Guest]: In fact, now, not even, you know, earlier one would have even thought.

01:32:50.580 --> 01:32:55.420
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps we will have another episode on that someday, like a fractal emerging out of this

01:32:55.420 --> 01:32:56.420
[Guest]: episode.

01:32:56.420 --> 01:33:03.820
[Guest]: So, you know, the interesting example here is what, so, you know, Sarada is a great example.

01:33:03.820 --> 01:33:09.340
[Guest]: Now, they managed to assure investors that their investments would be safe.

01:33:09.340 --> 01:33:14.740
[Guest]: What they did was they employed the agents of Peerless General Finance and Investment

01:33:14.740 --> 01:33:15.740
[Guest]: Company.

01:33:15.740 --> 01:33:20.180
[Guest]: Now, Peerless was a very popular investment company in parts of Eastern India.

01:33:20.180 --> 01:33:24.940
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, I remember very, very clearly, because, I mean, I grew up in Eastern India.

01:33:24.940 --> 01:33:30.140
[Guest]: Now, it had, it was, you know, it was formed in 1932, and had pioneered the collection

01:33:30.140 --> 01:33:34.260
[Guest]: of small savings in Eastern India, primarily in West Bengal.

01:33:34.260 --> 01:33:42.140
[Guest]: Now, what had happened was that RBI had forced Peerless to stop taking deposits in 2005-2006.

01:33:42.140 --> 01:33:47.620
[Guest]: And this led to a growth of unregulated deposit taking companies in West Bengal and other

01:33:47.620 --> 01:33:48.940
[Guest]: Eastern states.

01:33:48.940 --> 01:33:56.300
[Guest]: So agents of Peerless, who had always been trusted, because Peerless always repaid, became

01:33:56.300 --> 01:33:59.420
[Guest]: agents of Sarada, okay.

01:33:59.420 --> 01:34:04.260
[Guest]: And so basically, the the good brand name of, you know, Peerless, which sort of had

01:34:04.260 --> 01:34:11.580
[Guest]: been built over almost, almost seven decades, more than seven decades, rubbed on to, rubbed

01:34:11.580 --> 01:34:12.580
[Amit Varma]: on to Sarada.

01:34:12.580 --> 01:34:16.500
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, it's the same kind of thing we say home trade did by getting celebrity endorsements

01:34:16.500 --> 01:34:20.460
[Guest]: from Sachin and Shah Rukh and whatever that rubs off on to you.

01:34:20.460 --> 01:34:23.660
[Guest]: But in this case, what I'm talking about is the actual salesman.

01:34:23.660 --> 01:34:31.140
[Guest]: And how the, the herd mentality, sort of, how the trust factor came into the herd mentality,

01:34:31.140 --> 01:34:32.140
[Guest]: if that is.

01:34:32.140 --> 01:34:37.220
[Amit Varma]: No, and also, I guess, there's that natural tendency that once you have invested, you

01:34:37.220 --> 01:34:41.740
[Amit Varma]: will immediately rationalize your investment to yourself, you will double down on it, perhaps

01:34:41.740 --> 01:34:43.340
[Amit Varma]: even by investing more.

01:34:43.340 --> 01:34:48.900
[Amit Varma]: The endowment effect kicks in, where if you own, you know, one of these shares from one

01:34:48.900 --> 01:34:52.980
[Amit Varma]: of these companies, it immediately feels more valuable to you than it did when you did not

01:34:52.980 --> 01:34:54.340
[Amit Varma]: possess it.

01:34:54.340 --> 01:34:55.340
[Amit Varma]: And so on.

01:34:55.340 --> 01:35:02.100
[Guest]: So I just like to, you know, read out a small paragraph from the paper that I wrote many

01:35:02.100 --> 01:35:03.100
[Guest]: years back.

01:35:03.100 --> 01:35:08.540
[Guest]: Now, you know, it's essentially, obviously, you know, you're looking at what people you

01:35:08.540 --> 01:35:10.440
[Guest]: know, are doing.

01:35:10.440 --> 01:35:15.780
[Guest]: So this is something that we've written, and it's like the desire to conform to the behavior

01:35:15.780 --> 01:35:21.860
[Guest]: and opinions of others is a fundamental human trait, an accepted principle of psychology.

01:35:21.860 --> 01:35:26.980
[Guest]: If the people around the potential investor invest in a certain way, they might be a tendency

01:35:26.980 --> 01:35:33.100
[Guest]: for him to follow them, much like the circular mill of ants, okay, the mill is created when

01:35:33.100 --> 01:35:37.540
[Guest]: an army of ants find themselves separated from the colony.

01:35:37.540 --> 01:35:42.980
[Guest]: Once they're lost, they obey a simple rule, follow an ant in front of you.

01:35:42.980 --> 01:35:48.740
[Guest]: So decisions of investors, much like the circular mills of ants, are not made at the same time,

01:35:48.740 --> 01:35:50.140
[Guest]: but in a sequence.

01:35:50.140 --> 01:35:54.700
[Guest]: So people who invest in a Ponzi scheme assume that the scheme is a good bet, simply because

01:35:54.700 --> 01:35:58.280
[Guest]: some of the people they know have already invested in it.

01:35:58.280 --> 01:36:02.900
[Guest]: So everyone ends up making the wrong decisions, because the initial investors get into the

01:36:02.900 --> 01:36:06.340
[Guest]: scheme by chance, right?

01:36:06.340 --> 01:36:09.740
[Amit Varma]: And this reminds me of something EO Wilson once said, have you heard of the biologist

01:36:09.740 --> 01:36:10.740
[Amit Varma]: Edmundo Wilson?

01:36:10.740 --> 01:36:16.620
[Amit Varma]: No, there's a great quote by him about communism, where he says, quote, great idea, full stop

01:36:16.620 --> 01:36:18.820
[Amit Varma]: wrong species, stop quote.

01:36:18.820 --> 01:36:22.820
[Amit Varma]: And his idea was that low communism is a great idea for ants, which is specifically what

01:36:22.820 --> 01:36:29.140
[Amit Varma]: he meant ants and bees, because they are people who are wired to follow central planning commands

01:36:29.140 --> 01:36:35.580
[Amit Varma]: from on top and they all act as one body, but human nature being what it is, it cannot,

01:36:35.580 --> 01:36:37.540
[Amit Varma]: it simply cannot work.

01:36:37.540 --> 01:36:41.660
[Amit Varma]: So in that case, of course, drawing a distinction between ants and humans.

01:36:41.660 --> 01:36:45.540
[Amit Varma]: And the reason I made that whole point about no other species having Ponzi schemes, which

01:36:45.540 --> 01:36:48.420
[Amit Varma]: is of course, a glib and frivolous point.

01:36:48.420 --> 01:36:54.380
[Amit Varma]: But it is also true that as a species, because of our tendency to explain the world to ourselves,

01:36:54.380 --> 01:36:59.980
[Amit Varma]: because of narratives, all of these cognitive biases and these fallacies we tend to commit

01:36:59.980 --> 01:37:03.220
[Amit Varma]: are sort of hardwired into humans and no other species.

01:37:03.220 --> 01:37:06.300
[Amit Varma]: And all of them are useful in different contexts.

01:37:06.300 --> 01:37:11.220
[Amit Varma]: But when they go wrong, they sort of go wrong in these sort of ways.

01:37:11.220 --> 01:37:15.780
[Amit Varma]: In your paper, you've pointed out, you know, the recency effect, the anchoring effect and

01:37:15.780 --> 01:37:16.780
[Guest]: so on.

01:37:16.780 --> 01:37:21.340
[Guest]: The other interesting, you know, if we were to talk in millennial terms, there is also

01:37:21.340 --> 01:37:27.980
[Guest]: FOMO involved, you know, the fear of missing out on a good investment, the FOMO effect,

01:37:27.980 --> 01:37:28.980
[Amit Varma]: FOMO effect.

01:37:28.980 --> 01:37:29.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:37:29.980 --> 01:37:34.060
[Amit Varma]: The FOMO effect should now get into the language coined for the first time on the scene and

01:37:34.060 --> 01:37:35.060
[Guest]: the unseen.

01:37:35.060 --> 01:37:36.060
[Guest]: No, it's already there.

01:37:36.060 --> 01:37:37.060
[Amit Varma]: It's already there.

01:37:37.060 --> 01:37:38.060
[Guest]: FOMO is there.

01:37:38.060 --> 01:37:42.700
[Amit Varma]: But the FOMO effect to explain the FOMO effect to explain a proper noun should totally be

01:37:42.700 --> 01:37:43.700
[Amit Varma]: credited.

01:37:43.700 --> 01:37:44.700
[Amit Varma]: It is.

01:37:44.700 --> 01:37:45.700
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:37:45.700 --> 01:37:46.700
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

01:37:46.700 --> 01:37:47.700
[Guest]: So we are behavioral economists.

01:37:47.700 --> 01:37:48.700
[Amit Varma]: Now we have coined.

01:37:48.700 --> 01:37:49.700
[Amit Varma]: Who knows?

01:37:49.700 --> 01:37:54.540
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps one day we'll do an episode of economic funders on storytelling just about the FOMO

01:37:54.540 --> 01:37:55.540
[Amit Varma]: effect.

01:37:55.540 --> 01:37:56.540
[Guest]: It could happen.

01:37:56.540 --> 01:38:01.220
[Guest]: But then obviously, you know, there is first, as I said, is the herd mentality and then

01:38:01.220 --> 01:38:08.580
[Guest]: there is greed because, you know, you see that you compare the rate of returns on other

01:38:08.580 --> 01:38:10.500
[Guest]: investment which is available.

01:38:10.500 --> 01:38:15.180
[Guest]: And in this case, as I said, the returns available, returns which are offered on Ponzi schemes

01:38:15.180 --> 01:38:23.460
[Guest]: are generally significantly higher than the other schemes available in the market.

01:38:23.460 --> 01:38:29.100
[Guest]: So let me just give you a few schemes and then the kind of returns that they offered.

01:38:29.100 --> 01:38:34.660
[Guest]: So there was a Rose Valley Ponzi scheme in West Bengal a few years back that offered

01:38:34.660 --> 01:38:39.060
[Guest]: anywhere between 11.2 percent to 17.7 percent.

01:38:39.060 --> 01:38:42.380
[Guest]: PSCL offered 12.5 to 14 percent.

01:38:42.380 --> 01:38:47.700
[Guest]: Sarda reportedly offered returns on 17.5 to 22 percent.

01:38:47.700 --> 01:38:55.220
[Guest]: So and I mean, we've already seen the returns on offer in case of Speak Asia and MMM, you

01:38:55.220 --> 01:39:02.340
[Guest]: know, where a 5000 rupee investment was supposed to sort of become 3.4 crore at the end of

01:39:02.340 --> 01:39:03.340
[Guest]: the year.

01:39:03.340 --> 01:39:09.940
[Guest]: So basically, you know, with good advertising and stories of previous investors, as I said,

01:39:09.940 --> 01:39:14.020
[Guest]: you know, who made a killing by investing in the scheme, investors get caught in the

01:39:14.020 --> 01:39:20.740
[Guest]: euphoria that is generated and hand over their hard-earned money, much against going against

01:39:20.740 --> 01:39:21.740
[Guest]: common sense.

01:39:21.740 --> 01:39:27.340
[Guest]: And, you know, I'd like to quote this economic historian called Charles Kindleberger here.

01:39:27.340 --> 01:39:33.260
[Guest]: And this is what he said, there is nothing so disturbing to one's well-being and judgment

01:39:33.260 --> 01:39:36.380
[Guest]: as to see a friend get rich.

01:39:36.380 --> 01:39:44.580
[Guest]: So again, I mean, it's basically boils down to herd mentality and the fear of missing

01:39:44.580 --> 01:39:45.580
[Guest]: out.

01:39:45.580 --> 01:39:50.300
[Guest]: And overconfidence and over-optimism also have a role to play.

01:39:50.300 --> 01:39:55.780
[Guest]: As you said that, you know, once you are invested into something, you tend to rationalize that

01:39:55.780 --> 01:40:03.500
[Guest]: because I'm already in it, this is going to work out right, which may or may not.

01:40:03.500 --> 01:40:08.020
[Guest]: Then there is the contrast effect, wherein you compare with all the other available options

01:40:08.020 --> 01:40:11.860
[Guest]: and see that this is the best option going around.

01:40:11.860 --> 01:40:14.260
[Guest]: Mental accounting also plays a role.

01:40:14.260 --> 01:40:20.780
[Guest]: Now, mental accounting as you know, if regular listeners, have you discussed mental accounting?

01:40:20.780 --> 01:40:22.020
[Guest]: I'm sure you would have it in some way.

01:40:22.020 --> 01:40:26.700
[Amit Varma]: I haven't discussed mental accounting per se, but it's a subject of episode two of economic

01:40:26.700 --> 01:40:29.060
[Amit Varma]: funders now on Storytel.

01:40:29.060 --> 01:40:34.900
[Guest]: Once it is released today, I'm going to take every opportunity to plug it.

01:40:34.900 --> 01:40:38.380
[Amit Varma]: I'm not plugging a Ponzi scheme.

01:40:38.380 --> 01:40:44.220
[Amit Varma]: Free trial on Storytel, sign up at Storytel.com slash funders to just search for Amit Verma

01:40:44.220 --> 01:40:46.300
[Amit Varma]: or Vivek Kaul or economic funders.

01:40:46.300 --> 01:40:48.020
[Amit Varma]: Okay, we didn't plan this.

01:40:48.020 --> 01:40:52.180
[Amit Varma]: This wasn't a planned plug.

01:40:52.180 --> 01:40:57.540
[Guest]: So essentially, you know, what mental accounting was a term coined by Richard Thiller, as we

01:40:57.540 --> 01:40:58.540
[Guest]: as we know.

01:40:58.540 --> 01:41:04.620
[Guest]: And he defined it as the inclination to categorize and treat money differently, depending on

01:41:04.620 --> 01:41:09.020
[Guest]: where it comes from, and where it is kept and how it is spent.

01:41:09.020 --> 01:41:13.420
[Guest]: So basically, you know, gamblers who lose their winnings, for example, typically feel

01:41:13.420 --> 01:41:16.020
[Guest]: that they haven't lost anything.

01:41:16.020 --> 01:41:19.820
[Guest]: And though they would have been richer had they stopped while they were ahead, right?

01:41:19.820 --> 01:41:23.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the classic illustration of that is, let's say I sit down at a poker table

01:41:23.260 --> 01:41:28.500
[Amit Varma]: with a lakh, and I've turned it into two lakh, you know, so at the last hand of the day,

01:41:28.500 --> 01:41:33.340
[Amit Varma]: if I feel like gambling it up, I'll say, okay, I'll gamble with my one lakh winnings.

01:41:33.340 --> 01:41:37.380
[Amit Varma]: While the truth is, had I sat down right there with two lakhs, I would not have gambled with

01:41:37.380 --> 01:41:39.420
[Amit Varma]: an amount as big as a lakh.

01:41:39.420 --> 01:41:44.340
[Amit Varma]: But because I have, you know, created separate mental accounts for what I came with and what

01:41:44.340 --> 01:41:48.500
[Amit Varma]: I have won, you know, I am treating them differently.

01:41:48.500 --> 01:41:53.740
[Guest]: So similarly, in a Ponzi scheme, once investors have got a certain return on their investment,

01:41:53.740 --> 01:41:57.660
[Guest]: they do not hesitate to plow their returns back into the thing.

01:41:57.660 --> 01:42:03.100
[Guest]: So which is where mental accounting sort of comes into play.

01:42:03.100 --> 01:42:11.020
[Guest]: And obviously, I mean, the greater fool theory as we as we talked about, you know, in many

01:42:11.020 --> 01:42:13.660
[Guest]: cases, investors understand that it's a Ponzi scheme.

01:42:13.660 --> 01:42:17.980
[Amit Varma]: There's also sort of the Dunning-Kroger effect, which is a tendency of incompetent people

01:42:17.980 --> 01:42:20.700
[Amit Varma]: to think that they're better than they really are.

01:42:20.700 --> 01:42:24.340
[Amit Varma]: And that I think plays out, especially when it comes to the stock market, because people

01:42:24.340 --> 01:42:28.300
[Amit Varma]: will, for example, get a little half-baked knowledge, and then they will jharod that

01:42:28.300 --> 01:42:29.820
[Amit Varma]: wisdom to everyone.

01:42:29.820 --> 01:42:32.340
[Amit Varma]: And they will imagine them to be greater experts.

01:42:32.340 --> 01:42:36.700
[Amit Varma]: And they actually are on the basis of that half-baked knowledge, which helps them rationalize

01:42:36.700 --> 01:42:38.260
[Amit Varma]: the foolish investments they're making.

01:42:38.260 --> 01:42:40.180
[Guest]: And sometimes they're lucky they find it.

01:42:40.180 --> 01:42:46.500
[Amit Varma]: And in an environment if all stocks are going up, yeah, so they end up, you know, because

01:42:46.500 --> 01:42:49.980
[Amit Varma]: but I think most of the people who invest in a rising market tell themselves are making

01:42:49.980 --> 01:42:50.980
[Amit Varma]: good investments.

01:42:50.980 --> 01:42:55.420
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, they don't think about it as you know, it is I know this investment is stupid in

01:42:55.420 --> 01:42:59.860
[Amit Varma]: terms of fundamental value, but it is rational because the likelihood of a greater fool is

01:42:59.860 --> 01:43:00.860
[Amit Varma]: very high.

01:43:00.860 --> 01:43:03.780
[Amit Varma]: But you know, I could respect an investor like that.

01:43:03.780 --> 01:43:07.340
[Amit Varma]: But I don't think most investors think like that way.

01:43:07.340 --> 01:43:12.380
[Guest]: So yeah, so obviously, the greater fool theory is also at play, wherein, you know, some of

01:43:12.380 --> 01:43:16.860
[Guest]: the investors and I have, you know, over the years met a lot of these investors who know

01:43:16.860 --> 01:43:20.980
[Guest]: that they're dealing with a Ponzi scheme, but they still go ahead because the entire

01:43:20.980 --> 01:43:24.980
[Guest]: the feeling is that, you know, they will be able to get out the music playing you have

01:43:24.980 --> 01:43:29.140
[Guest]: to dance before before the scheme collapses.

01:43:29.140 --> 01:43:37.460
[Guest]: So these are some of the behavioral so called aspects which play a huge role, which sort

01:43:37.460 --> 01:43:42.940
[Guest]: of, I mean, gets people to invest in a Ponzi scheme over and over again.

01:43:42.940 --> 01:43:47.380
[Guest]: And I think the what also happens is, I mean, this has got nothing to do with behavioral

01:43:47.380 --> 01:43:48.380
[Guest]: aspects.

01:43:48.380 --> 01:43:54.300
[Guest]: I mean, as we discussed a little earlier, you know, in most cases, we don't come to

01:43:54.300 --> 01:43:58.620
[Guest]: know as to even you know, even when these frauds are caught, we don't know as to what

01:43:58.620 --> 01:43:59.620
[Guest]: happens to them.

01:43:59.620 --> 01:44:02.140
[Guest]: I mean, take a case like speak Asia, right?

01:44:02.140 --> 01:44:03.340
[Guest]: The scheme collapsed.

01:44:03.340 --> 01:44:06.180
[Guest]: And you know, what happened to the guys who were running the scheme?

01:44:06.180 --> 01:44:09.540
[Guest]: I mean, did the people get their money back?

01:44:09.540 --> 01:44:15.900
[Guest]: So it's very important that this information also comes back to us.

01:44:15.900 --> 01:44:20.820
[Guest]: Because, you know, if the people who are running these frauds are not getting punished, I mean,

01:44:20.820 --> 01:44:27.220
[Guest]: what stops people from, you know, running more of these frauds over and over again,

01:44:27.220 --> 01:44:31.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if any editors of financial papers are listening, maybe that's a whole new feature.

01:44:31.020 --> 01:44:34.580
[Amit Varma]: You could do one of these weekends about what happened to fraudsters of the past.

01:44:34.580 --> 01:44:39.940
[Guest]: I mean, everyone from like, I mean, we do sort of, you know, people do get to know what

01:44:39.940 --> 01:44:42.780
[Guest]: a, you know, Ketan Parekh is up to.

01:44:42.780 --> 01:44:48.420
[Guest]: But Ketan Parekh was like this one big guy who, you know, who ran a scam and essentially

01:44:48.420 --> 01:44:54.500
[Guest]: borrowed money from Madhya Pradesh Cooperative Bank and diverted it into the stock market

01:44:54.500 --> 01:44:58.700
[Guest]: and pushed up what were then called the K10 stocks.

01:44:58.700 --> 01:45:01.180
[Guest]: Obviously, you know, his game ran out.

01:45:01.180 --> 01:45:04.780
[Guest]: But I mean, but then there are so many of these small Ponzi schemes which are around

01:45:04.780 --> 01:45:10.020
[Guest]: and a lot of them are MLM Ponzi schemes where money is lost.

01:45:10.020 --> 01:45:15.300
[Guest]: But one really never comes to know as to what happens to the guys who, you know, ran these

01:45:15.300 --> 01:45:16.300
[Guest]: schemes.

01:45:16.300 --> 01:45:23.260
[Guest]: So, so a lot of the guys who run these Ponzi schemes, you know, have a halo effect around

01:45:23.260 --> 01:45:24.260
[Guest]: them.

01:45:24.260 --> 01:45:28.220
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they have this infectious optimism, wealth creators, you know, we're going to

01:45:28.220 --> 01:45:32.540
[Guest]: do this and we're going to get this right and, and, and obviously, you know, the media

01:45:32.540 --> 01:45:39.580
[Guest]: loves, the media loves heroes, I mean, they make heroes only to sort of pull them down

01:45:39.580 --> 01:45:40.580
[Guest]: later.

01:45:40.580 --> 01:45:47.220
[Guest]: So, I remember of this, this, this quote, by this gentleman called C. Natesan, who ran

01:45:47.220 --> 01:45:49.700
[Guest]: the Anubhav Plantation scheme.

01:45:49.700 --> 01:45:56.940
[Guest]: So Natesan basically, you know, said that, I mean, so he sort of tried selling himself

01:45:56.940 --> 01:46:04.060
[Guest]: and his companies as someone who always was interested in planting trees and had now turned

01:46:04.060 --> 01:46:07.060
[Guest]: it into a business.

01:46:07.060 --> 01:46:08.700
[Guest]: So I always wanted to plant trees.

01:46:08.700 --> 01:46:13.420
[Guest]: As a child, I used to feel sad seeing trees burned down in my village in Tirunelveli.

01:46:13.420 --> 01:46:19.180
[Guest]: Now, again, I mean, and then, I mean, we all remember Harshad Mehta, right?

01:46:19.180 --> 01:46:23.900
[Guest]: So Harshad Mehta's scam was also like a Ponzi scheme, wherein he was siphoning off money

01:46:23.900 --> 01:46:28.700
[Guest]: from banks and, you know, then diverting it into the stock market and siphoning off more

01:46:28.700 --> 01:46:32.740
[Guest]: money from banks and, you know, diverting it again into the stock market and, you know,

01:46:32.740 --> 01:46:35.580
[Guest]: then, you know, he kept driving up the prices.

01:46:35.580 --> 01:46:41.340
[Guest]: So he apparently remarked once, in an interview, wherein he said that I thought I'd be like

01:46:41.340 --> 01:46:47.980
[Guest]: Pied Piper, I thought I can sell dreams, that asset creation is not a crime, that if you

01:46:47.980 --> 01:46:50.540
[Guest]: want to be Harshad Mehta, come to the stock market.

01:46:50.540 --> 01:46:57.060
[Guest]: Now, I mean, you know, this is such a, you know, optimistic thing to say, inspirational

01:46:57.060 --> 01:46:58.060
[Amit Varma]: quote.

01:46:58.060 --> 01:47:00.140
[Amit Varma]: Hero of the common people.

01:47:00.140 --> 01:47:05.100
[Guest]: And which is why I mean, this, this sort of, you know, gets us back to the social media.

01:47:05.100 --> 01:47:08.900
[Guest]: And I don't know if it happens to you, it happens to me all the time where this random

01:47:08.900 --> 01:47:13.960
[Guest]: guy will come in and say, you know, if this, you know, why do you keep saying these negative

01:47:13.960 --> 01:47:15.820
[Guest]: things and spoil the environment?

01:47:15.820 --> 01:47:20.180
[Guest]: And why don't you talk about positive things and, you know, all this.

01:47:20.180 --> 01:47:24.580
[Amit Varma]: And the job of journalists anyway, is to afflict the comfortable and comfort the afflicted.

01:47:24.580 --> 01:47:25.580
[Guest]: So you know,

01:47:25.580 --> 01:47:29.860
[Guest]: And more than that, I mean, it's not my job to, you know, make you happy in life.

01:47:29.860 --> 01:47:32.140
[Amit Varma]: But we have a remarkable episode 12 dream reforms.

01:47:32.140 --> 01:47:33.140
[Guest]: Yes, we did that.

01:47:33.140 --> 01:47:35.420
[Guest]: I mean, if people didn't, yeah.

01:47:35.420 --> 01:47:37.660
[Guest]: So we give solutions also.

01:47:37.660 --> 01:47:44.260
[Amit Varma]: But I think it's more of a job to sort of talk about all the things that are going wrong.

01:47:44.260 --> 01:47:48.900
[Amit Varma]: So people know about them, because acknowledging the problem is at least a first step to a

01:47:48.900 --> 01:47:49.900
[Amit Varma]: solution.

01:47:49.900 --> 01:47:53.980
[Guest]: My aforementioned question, sorry, how do you sort of before you cut in my aforementioned

01:47:53.980 --> 01:47:59.860
[Amit Varma]: question to which I think is a legit question, which is that listen, yeah, most people do

01:47:59.860 --> 01:48:04.580
[Amit Varma]: not have the cognitive bandwidth in terms of the time I mean, they're busy doing their

01:48:04.580 --> 01:48:05.580
[Amit Varma]: everyday things.

01:48:05.580 --> 01:48:09.700
[Amit Varma]: They don't have the cognitive bandwidth to take decisions on complex subjects like where

01:48:09.700 --> 01:48:11.860
[Amit Varma]: should they invest their money and so on.

01:48:11.860 --> 01:48:16.020
[Amit Varma]: My advice to people, for example, about the stock market always is and I think you'd agree

01:48:16.020 --> 01:48:20.500
[Amit Varma]: with me is that unless you have studied it in great depth, don't invest in the stock

01:48:20.500 --> 01:48:21.500
[Amit Varma]: market at all.

01:48:21.500 --> 01:48:24.660
[Amit Varma]: Because otherwise, you're one of the suckers like in poker, they say if you don't know

01:48:24.660 --> 01:48:27.140
[Amit Varma]: who's the sucker at the table, it's you.

01:48:27.140 --> 01:48:31.660
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, most people now don't have the time to get that kind of detailed knowledge.

01:48:31.660 --> 01:48:35.660
[Amit Varma]: They rely on all of these instincts, which you earlier mentioned, look around you what

01:48:35.660 --> 01:48:40.380
[Amit Varma]: are successful people apparently doing, there is, you know, the FOMO effect comes into play

01:48:40.380 --> 01:48:42.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth.

01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:46.820
[Amit Varma]: So now if someone is to ask you that, listen, yeah, Vivek, I have a, I spend all my time

01:48:46.820 --> 01:48:53.180
[Amit Varma]: and all my mental energy on making a living at whatever I do now, when I look to invest

01:48:53.180 --> 01:48:58.100
[Amit Varma]: or when these kinds of opportunities come up, what are the heuristics, which I should

01:48:58.100 --> 01:49:01.940
[Amit Varma]: apply to make sure that I am not being fooled?

01:49:01.940 --> 01:49:04.580
[Amit Varma]: You know, what are the kinds of heuristics which I can look at?

01:49:04.580 --> 01:49:08.980
[Amit Varma]: And I'll take a short at, you know, two quick answers which come to my mind, and then you

01:49:08.980 --> 01:49:11.460
[Amit Varma]: can elaborate and give more of your own.

01:49:11.460 --> 01:49:15.120
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is, there is no such thing as a free lunch.

01:49:15.120 --> 01:49:18.780
[Amit Varma]: If someone is offering you, for example, far greater rate of returns and everybody else

01:49:18.780 --> 01:49:23.420
[Amit Varma]: in the market, they must, you know, it fails a smell test, ask yourself, why that would

01:49:23.420 --> 01:49:24.820
[Amit Varma]: be.

01:49:24.820 --> 01:49:29.900
[Amit Varma]: And the other heuristic I'd offer is that, again, it's a cliche, if it feels too good

01:49:29.900 --> 01:49:35.580
[Amit Varma]: to be true, it probably is, you know, these are my two heuristics that I would offer what

01:49:35.580 --> 01:49:36.580
[Guest]: are yours?

01:49:36.580 --> 01:49:37.580
[Guest]: Okay.

01:49:37.580 --> 01:49:45.420
[Guest]: I agree with you 100% on that, I mean, so anyone, so I would sort of put it in a slightly

01:49:45.420 --> 01:49:46.500
[Guest]: more technical term.

01:49:46.500 --> 01:49:55.220
[Guest]: So the moment anyone other than a bank, okay, guarantees you a rate of return, you know

01:49:55.220 --> 01:49:56.220
[Guest]: you're being fooled.

01:49:56.220 --> 01:49:59.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's very, very clear there.

01:49:59.480 --> 01:50:01.200
[Guest]: So you have to be careful about that.

01:50:01.200 --> 01:50:07.740
[Guest]: The second thing is also, you know, you look at the fact that if, let's say banks are offering

01:50:07.740 --> 01:50:13.020
[Guest]: a rate of interest of 7%, 6% or whatever, as they are right now.

01:50:13.020 --> 01:50:23.020
[Guest]: So in that market, if someone's offering you a return of, let's say, 15% or 20%, you know

01:50:23.020 --> 01:50:28.820
[Guest]: that there is something wrong there.

01:50:28.820 --> 01:50:32.940
[Guest]: Other than that, you know, so other than I think more than heuristics, you know, I have

01:50:32.940 --> 01:50:43.020
[Guest]: these 10 points, which I think are useful for anyone who wants to generally plan their

01:50:43.020 --> 01:50:44.020
[Guest]: personal finance.

01:50:44.020 --> 01:50:48.060
[Guest]: And so, if you're okay with that, I can…

01:50:48.060 --> 01:50:50.460
[Amit Varma]: Please, please give us all 10 points.

01:50:50.460 --> 01:50:57.580
[Guest]: So okay, now, I mean, before I get into the 10, I'll first give you some of the most basic

01:50:57.580 --> 01:50:58.580
[Guest]: points.

01:50:58.580 --> 01:51:05.660
[Guest]: So the most basic point in investing is never have all your eggs in one basket.

01:51:05.660 --> 01:51:13.940
[Guest]: And this is, when I say this, I mean this within investments and across investments.

01:51:13.940 --> 01:51:18.060
[Guest]: So what it basically means is that if, okay, you don't want to do anything in the world,

01:51:18.060 --> 01:51:22.580
[Guest]: you want to just deposit money in a bank, please don't go and deposit all your money

01:51:22.580 --> 01:51:23.580
[Guest]: in one bank.

01:51:23.580 --> 01:51:27.060
[Guest]: I mean, that is by far the most stupid thing you can do.

01:51:27.060 --> 01:51:31.140
[Guest]: I mean, after that, you can't claim that you know, you are financially illiterate and you're

01:51:31.140 --> 01:51:32.140
[Guest]: not very sophisticated.

01:51:32.140 --> 01:51:37.420
[Guest]: And I mean, I find it, I mean, if you're educated enough to open a bank account, then you need

01:51:37.420 --> 01:51:40.700
[Guest]: to be educated enough to not have all your money in one bank.

01:51:40.700 --> 01:51:42.940
[Amit Varma]: At this point, Vivek has a slight smile on his face.

01:51:42.940 --> 01:51:47.260
[Amit Varma]: At this point, I will inform my listeners very sheepishly that time and again, Vivek

01:51:47.260 --> 01:51:51.740
[Amit Varma]: has berated me, because I have only one bank account, which is an HDFC bank, and I keep

01:51:51.740 --> 01:51:53.820
[Amit Varma]: telling him it won't shut down.

01:51:53.820 --> 01:51:57.820
[Amit Varma]: But even if people take the money in that there is so little of it that who cares, buy

01:51:57.820 --> 01:52:02.420
[Guest]: something nice, buy some vada pavs, kindly continue with other points.

01:52:02.420 --> 01:52:05.140
[Guest]: So that's the, you know, the most basic point.

01:52:05.140 --> 01:52:10.340
[Guest]: And I mean, if I mean, look at what has been happening with the PMC bank, and some of the

01:52:10.340 --> 01:52:14.780
[Guest]: videos floating around and people you know, there are people saying I had only 25 lakhs

01:52:14.780 --> 01:52:17.580
[Guest]: and all of it was in the in this bank.

01:52:17.580 --> 01:52:22.980
[Guest]: Now, I mean, if you had 25 lakhs, and if you had the ability to earn those 25 lakhs, why

01:52:22.980 --> 01:52:24.900
[Guest]: did you have all of it in one bank account?

01:52:24.900 --> 01:52:30.140
[Guest]: I mean, I find it a little, you know, when people sort of, and especially in an era where

01:52:30.140 --> 01:52:36.140
[Guest]: people spend so much time and energy in planning a holiday and but the moment they have to

01:52:36.140 --> 01:52:40.540
[Guest]: plan their money, you know, all their faculties go for a toss.

01:52:40.540 --> 01:52:44.660
[Guest]: I mean, I know so many people who spend weeks planning a holiday.

01:52:44.660 --> 01:52:48.580
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, you can spend one day planning your finances as well.

01:52:48.580 --> 01:52:49.940
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's not going to hurt you in any way.

01:52:49.940 --> 01:52:54.060
[Guest]: I just bought a new phone, and I spent so much time researching that I could have like,

01:52:54.060 --> 01:52:57.740
[Guest]: so one of the things that I do in life, you know, when I need to buy a phone, I don't

01:52:57.740 --> 01:53:00.740
[Guest]: do any research, I have a price point.

01:53:00.740 --> 01:53:05.620
[Guest]: And I see as to you know, who's within that price point, which are the largest selling

01:53:05.620 --> 01:53:08.420
[Guest]: phones, and I go and buy that phone.

01:53:08.420 --> 01:53:12.380
[Guest]: Because if so many people are already making that mistake, you know, I can as well.

01:53:12.380 --> 01:53:17.140
[Amit Varma]: And since our listeners are getting a bonanza of free funders from us during the show, I

01:53:17.140 --> 01:53:21.780
[Amit Varma]: will offer another nugget Have you heard of this term called satisficing?

01:53:21.780 --> 01:53:26.660
[Amit Varma]: So satisficing is a portmanteau term, which is like, it's a combination of two existing

01:53:26.660 --> 01:53:29.740
[Amit Varma]: words, satisfying, and sufficing.

01:53:29.740 --> 01:53:35.780
[Amit Varma]: And the concept comes from the fact that decisions tire us out, every decision takes a certain

01:53:35.780 --> 01:53:40.420
[Amit Varma]: amount of energy, leaving less energy for other decisions and indeed other work.

01:53:40.420 --> 01:53:45.220
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of people fight this what is known as decision fatigue, by satisficing when it

01:53:45.220 --> 01:53:46.220
[Amit Varma]: comes to purchases.

01:53:46.220 --> 01:53:49.260
[Amit Varma]: So if you're doing a major purchase, like you're buying a house, obviously, you spend

01:53:49.260 --> 01:53:50.740
[Amit Varma]: the time to research that.

01:53:50.740 --> 01:53:55.100
[Amit Varma]: But if you're buying a phone, or if you're buying a book, or if you're buying, you know,

01:53:55.100 --> 01:53:59.940
[Amit Varma]: any electronic implement, then you know, you know that all the brands and all the categories

01:53:59.940 --> 01:54:00.940
[Amit Varma]: are more or less okay.

01:54:00.940 --> 01:54:07.440
[Amit Varma]: So you satisfy, you satisfy yourself with the first one that appears to suffice.

01:54:07.440 --> 01:54:09.860
[Amit Varma]: And it's called satisficing.

01:54:09.860 --> 01:54:15.140
[Amit Varma]: And and in fact, decision fatigue is also a reason, for example, why people like Steve

01:54:15.140 --> 01:54:19.500
[Amit Varma]: Jobs, and now Mark Zuckerberg, they dress the same way every day, it feels like a uniform

01:54:19.500 --> 01:54:22.060
[Guest]: like for Steve Jobs, it was a black belt.

01:54:22.060 --> 01:54:25.100
[Guest]: That was something that you don't have to take a decision, there was something that

01:54:25.100 --> 01:54:30.140
[Amit Varma]: Albert Einstein started, Einstein started, there you go, it comes from the finest minds

01:54:30.140 --> 01:54:32.780
[Guest]: that he wanted to save his mental energy.

01:54:32.780 --> 01:54:34.940
[Guest]: I think he had seven suits of the same kind.

01:54:34.940 --> 01:54:35.940
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:54:35.940 --> 01:54:39.220
[Guest]: Because he didn't want to spend time figuring out what to wear.

01:54:39.220 --> 01:54:44.020
[Guest]: So in fact, I do that in my own little way, I have three shirts of the same kind.

01:54:44.020 --> 01:54:50.500
[Amit Varma]: Ditto, I mean, I in fact, if you notice, last year, during my keto diet, I just cycled between

01:54:50.500 --> 01:54:52.980
[Amit Varma]: black t shirts and jeans.

01:54:52.980 --> 01:54:54.780
[Guest]: So it just keeps the life.

01:54:54.780 --> 01:54:58.860
[Guest]: I mean, for jeans, I have just two pairs of jeans, and I just keep changing it to I have

01:54:58.860 --> 01:55:04.260
[Amit Varma]: more, but I use just to figure out what to wear.

01:55:04.260 --> 01:55:08.620
[Guest]: Okay, so now, also, neither of us can afford more given the times we live.

01:55:08.620 --> 01:55:10.300
[Guest]: Yes, I mean, yeah, we are.

01:55:10.300 --> 01:55:13.100
[Guest]: I think we should start asking for donations also.

01:55:13.100 --> 01:55:16.220
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of bubbles, I should ask you about the online journalism bubble at some point,

01:55:16.220 --> 01:55:17.220
[Amit Varma]: but let that pass.

01:55:17.220 --> 01:55:18.220
[Guest]: Let's continue.

01:55:18.220 --> 01:55:19.220
[Guest]: What's your second point?

01:55:19.220 --> 01:55:20.220
[Guest]: No.

01:55:20.220 --> 01:55:21.220
[Guest]: So these are, these are the 10 main points.

01:55:21.220 --> 01:55:26.140
[Guest]: I mean, other than, you know, I didn't put I didn't want to put the diversification point

01:55:26.140 --> 01:55:28.260
[Guest]: into this, because it's just very, very basic.

01:55:28.260 --> 01:55:29.260
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:55:29.260 --> 01:55:32.300
[Guest]: So if you can't even do that, then I mean, God help you.

01:55:32.300 --> 01:55:37.380
[Guest]: So if your family is dependent on you, buy a term insurance policy.

01:55:37.380 --> 01:55:42.100
[Guest]: If no one is dependent on you, you don't need insurance, okay?

01:55:42.100 --> 01:55:46.980
[Guest]: Stay away from investment plans, which pretend to be insurance, endowment, money back, you

01:55:46.980 --> 01:55:49.340
[Guest]: lips, life will be very simple.

01:55:49.340 --> 01:55:53.420
[Guest]: Buy a house if you're planning to live in it.

01:55:53.420 --> 01:55:56.740
[Guest]: Stay away from under construction properties as far as possible.

01:55:56.740 --> 01:56:01.960
[Guest]: Further, try to buy an apartment in a society where people are already living.

01:56:01.960 --> 01:56:06.060
[Guest]: So that if there is some, you know, bureaucratic or administrative problem, you're not the

01:56:06.060 --> 01:56:09.140
[Guest]: only one running around, when there are other people involved.

01:56:09.140 --> 01:56:14.820
[Guest]: And in India, it is very, very important because, you know, all societies have some lafda at

01:56:14.820 --> 01:56:16.940
[Guest]: the end of the day.

01:56:16.940 --> 01:56:20.380
[Guest]: Have a health insurance policy for your entire family.

01:56:20.380 --> 01:56:25.820
[Guest]: To meet emergencies, have some money in a bank account, which could meet expenses of

01:56:25.820 --> 01:56:28.780
[Guest]: three to six months, I mean, at the very basic.

01:56:28.780 --> 01:56:34.660
[Guest]: If you want the ability to make decisions that you feel are correct, at any point of

01:56:34.660 --> 01:56:39.180
[Guest]: time in your life, you need at least two years of expenses in the bank account.

01:56:39.180 --> 01:56:46.580
[Guest]: I mean, then you can, you know, ask your boss to fuck off and do what the right thing is,

01:56:46.580 --> 01:56:48.000
[Guest]: what you feel the right thing is.

01:56:48.000 --> 01:56:50.740
[Guest]: But without that, you can't.

01:56:50.740 --> 01:56:57.060
[Guest]: Have an SIP running on a few good equity mutual funds, review the performance once a year.

01:56:57.060 --> 01:57:00.460
[Guest]: Don't go looking at the returns every week, a lot of people do that.

01:57:00.460 --> 01:57:05.860
[Guest]: If not every week, at least they have a tendency to look at every month.

01:57:05.860 --> 01:57:09.660
[Guest]: There is good research that shows that people who look at their returns regularly tend to

01:57:09.660 --> 01:57:13.980
[Guest]: invest in equity for shorter terms than people who don't, and which basically means then

01:57:13.980 --> 01:57:16.540
[Guest]: you lose out on returns.

01:57:16.540 --> 01:57:19.260
[Guest]: After a certain age, make a will.

01:57:19.260 --> 01:57:23.620
[Guest]: Also make sure that when it comes to all your investments, nominations are in place.

01:57:23.620 --> 01:57:27.540
[Guest]: Because I mean, I have seen a few issues of where, you know, the husband has died and

01:57:27.540 --> 01:57:33.520
[Guest]: the wife has no idea where he had invested and, and it's too late to sort of start again

01:57:33.520 --> 01:57:35.820
[Guest]: from scratch.

01:57:35.820 --> 01:57:39.740
[Guest]: Make your tax saving investments at the beginning of the year, if you're investing in things

01:57:39.740 --> 01:57:43.180
[Guest]: like public provident fund, or do them through the year.

01:57:43.180 --> 01:57:47.460
[Guest]: If you're investing in things like let's say a tax saving mutual fund, don't wake up in

01:57:47.460 --> 01:57:51.420
[Guest]: the last week of the year to make your tax saving investment when you're more likely

01:57:51.420 --> 01:57:56.340
[Guest]: to be taken for a ride because you'll end up investing in anything, you know, anyone

01:57:56.340 --> 01:58:01.580
[Guest]: who basically comes to your house and just gets you to sign whatever paper they want

01:58:01.580 --> 01:58:03.180
[Guest]: to.

01:58:03.180 --> 01:58:07.260
[Guest]: Also be careful when you go to a bank for anything, because these days, they you know,

01:58:07.260 --> 01:58:10.920
[Guest]: the moment you enter a bank, they want to sell you things that you don't need.

01:58:10.920 --> 01:58:15.320
[Guest]: Make sure that you end up doing what you had gone there for, okay.

01:58:15.320 --> 01:58:19.440
[Guest]: So I mean, the example like I like to give here is that someone sold a pension plan to

01:58:19.440 --> 01:58:26.020
[Guest]: my father a few weeks before he was retiring, okay, so thankfully, I found out and you know,

01:58:26.020 --> 01:58:31.500
